<SLUG> BC-Russia-Crime </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian organized crime affects at least 26 countries
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian organized crime gangs are active in at
least 26 countries, a top law enforcement official said Tuesday,
according to the ITAR-Tass news agency.
	   Col. Vladimir Selivanov, head of the Interior Ministry's
organized crime department, said the countries in which Russian
organized crime is most active are the United States, Germany,
Switzerland, Israel, Turkey and the Netherlands.
	   Most groups focus on crimes including money laundering, bank
fraud, drug trafficking, kidnapping, and smuggling alcohol,
strategic materials, arms and automobiles.
	   Selivanov also blamed foreign nationals illegally residing in
Russia for some of the country's crime problems. He said crimes by
foreigners increased 27 percent in the first quarter of 1998
compared with last year.
	   (mr/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
