<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Rose,0256 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Teenage golf sensation confirms he's turning professional
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HILVERSUM, Netherlands (AP) _ Justin Rose, the 17-year-old
English golfer who shot to fame by coming in fourth in the British
Open, confirmed Tuesday that he has turned professional.
	   Rose, who missed out on a 69,875-pound (dlrs 114,874) pay day
because he played the British Open as an amateur, will start his
first tournament as a professional Thursday when he tees off in the
Dutch Open.
	   ``Since my early childhood I have always wanted to play
professional golf,'' Rose said in a press release issued by
Scottish-based Carnegie Sports Management, the management group
that is overseeing his professional career.
	   ``I have had an enjoyable and rewarding career as an amateur and
I have a great deal of positives to take into the professional
ranks. I am very excited about the challenges and experiences that
lie ahead,'' Rose added.
	   Rose's 1-under-par 69 in Sunday's final round at the Royal
Birkdale club left Rose two shots behind Open winner Mark O'Meara
who beat Brian Watts in a playoff and one place behind Tiger Woods.
His performance was the best by an amateur at the British Open
since 1953.
	   Rose's pro career begins Thursday, a week short of his 18th
birthday, when he joins a field including the likes of Phil
Mickelson, Lee Westwood and Nick Price chasing the 475,000 guilders
(dlrs 219,145) winner's cheque at the Hilversumsche course outside
this town 40 kilometers (25 miles) east of Amsterdam. 	   
</TEXT>
