<SLUG> BC-Portugal-Strikes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gas tanker drivers reject deal to end strike, harbor pilots walk
</HEADLINE>
out &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Gas tanker truck drivers on Tuesday
rejected a deal to end their two-day strike, while harbor pilots
began a 14-day stoppage which the government said could mean ``huge
losses'' for the country.
	   Labor leaders representing the 2,000 striking tanker drivers had
persuaded government officials and employers to agree to review
written testing procedures _ the strikers' main demand.
	   But the striking truckers were not convinced by the deal
negotiated by their leaders during a three-hour meeting, and
rejected the proposal. They asked for more information about the
proposed review and further talks.
	   Meanwhile, some gas pumps in major cities were already running
dry, and the National Association of Gas Vendors said up to 70
percent of gas stations could be out of supplies on Wednesday.
	   Labor unrest also seriously disrupted imports and exports by sea
Tuesday _ the first of a 14-day stoppage by the country's 80 harbor
pilots who are responsible for steering large vessels into ports.
	   The pilots, whose action effectively closed ports to cargo
ships, demand the right to set their own working conditions.
	   Recent legislation forced them under the supervision of higher
officials and Infrastructure Minister Joao Cravinho told reporters
that the government ``would not yield'' to the pressure.
	   ``Only in a Banana republic can 80 individuals bend the country
to their corporate interests'' he said.
	   Cravinho said more than 90 percent of harbor pilots were under
investigation for corruption, extortion and criminal association
linked to their work before it came under senior supervision. Of
the 30 pilots at Lisbon port, 22 are currently suspended pending
the outcome of police investigations.
	   The pilots also want a 5 percent pay hike, a risk subsidy and
revised career scales.
	   (bh/jt)
</TEXT>
