<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Fashion, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chanel's Triumphant New Looks at Couture
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Lacroix, Feraud shows &QL; 
 &UR; With APPhotos &QL; 
 &UR; By SUZY PATTERSON &QC; 
 &UR; AP Fashion Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Karl Lagerfeld's Tuesday fall-winter couture show
for Chanel was a triumph of innovative true haute couture over the
siren temptations of blitz-the-media showmanship seen this week --
notably at Givenchy and Dior.
	   For a few years now, Lagerfeld has given up his own shock-wave
clothes that made their eyes pop at Chanel to serve the true
clients here in a kinder, gentler way.
	   Shown on the shop at Rue Cambon, it was exciting just to watch
real clothes, such as a tweed suit with hidden buttons, scoop neck,
a long pin-tuck pleated skirt, to the ankle tops.
	   The skirts were almost all long and full, but there were many
beautifully-cut slim jackets fastened by new ``chain link'' buttons
that could be worn with any length skirt.
	   It all looked glamorous, with legendary Naomi Campbell modeling
one of the adorable full-skirted suits with an opening and silk
panel in back. She and Linda Evangelista were the ``big sisters to
most this group that included younger models like fiery-haired
Karen Elsen ad Crystelle St. Louis.
	   Fabrics like soft boucles in hazy shades of gray and creamy tan
were also paired with floaty silk camisole blouses, that turned
into jackets in some outfits.
	   U.S. merchandisers were enthusiastic: ``I loved it.'' said
Nicole Fischelis, fashion director of Saks. ``The new proportions,
the gracefulness of the trumpet flared skirts. It was totally
elegant.''
	   ``And can be worn by several kinds of figure,'' added Joan Kaner
of Nieman Marcus.
	   The gleam of silvery threads lit up some suits, an occasional
brick wool dress with blouson top came just below the knee, for
those who would rather go short.
	   Towards late-day, the Chanel girls slipped into feathery-light
clothes, sometimes a black lacy suit with an easy, flared jacket, a
light and easy skirt, just above the ankle.
	   ``These clothes are meant to be proud, dignified and natural''
Lagerfeld's program announced, and yes, that was the spirit.
	   Tuxedo ideas looked so feminine with the looser bolero or
camisole-inspired tops. An incredible gray jersey evening dress
with plunging neckline and gold-button shoulder details, and a
trumpet skirt with panels was the ultimate in chic.
	   Marabou trim on dramatic capes, delicate beaded dresses,
all-over beaded models and starry astral themes on tulle or lace
were outstanding for the Chanel girl making a grand entrance.
	   Accessories? Simple and unique: the flat black sandals with
slightly open fronts looked perfect with these long, full clothes.
A cashmere bouclette boa rolled around those loose camisoles looked
good, like the low chain belts for long, full skirts.
	   Christian Lacroix's collection starts at cocktail time, with a
dark boucle suit with scattered checks and pearly satin lining, or
a suit with white off-shoulder jacket and coral satin skirt.
	   But evening dresses are where this couturier's great creativity
comes out, this time based largely on 17th-century Spanish
painting.
	   The lace over lace, the feather inserts, the black dresses with
arabesques all had a Spanish, but not costumey, air. There was
refreshing color throughout, from parma violets through old gold,
bright crimsons and buttercup yellow taffeta.
	   Silhouettes were blessedly simplified compared with past
extravagant outfits.
	   One sensational number was the strapless turquoise brocade with
its big jeweled scarab pin and cape-coat gathered in back. And the
shimmering ``Infanta'' bride with her puffy sleeves, tiny waist and
skirt over an iridescent red underskirt was sheer beauty.
	   At Louis Feraud, his daughter Kiki, chief designer since Feraud
retired, also liked party clothes and clearly shares with her
father a love of color, fun and themes.
	   She also likes race tracks -- an ``elegant sport,'' she says.
	   Indeed some of the clothes in this rich collection had the
``derriere'' interest and curvy silhouette of the sidesaddle riders
of old but, this time, with plenty of bright colors, feathers and
sparkles.
	   Ivana Trump, in the audience wearing a fitted silk cyclamen
short suit, didn't seem to fall for any one look here but said she
was pleased: ``I saw much of interest, a beautiful use of color.''
	   (sp-dgs-eg)
</TEXT>
