<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-US-Nuclear, 4th Ld-Writethru,0671 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan and U.S. hoping to bridge gaps in crucial talks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: UPDATES with brief foreign ministry statement, Pakistan pushes
for international mediation in Kashmir dispute; INCORPORATES
India-Nuclear, India-Nuclear Relations; TRIMS &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos ISL102-5
 &UR; By KATHY GANNON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ On the first day of talks aimed at
bridging differences with the United States, Pakistan argued
Tuesday against the U.S.-led economic sanctions prompted by nuclear
testing .
	   U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, who arrived in
Pakistan from India, is on a mission aimed at preempting a nuclear
arms race in South Asia, following the underground nuclear tests
that the uneasy neighbors conducted last May.
	   ``Pakistan understands US concerns over the increasing threat of
an arms race and escalation, and welcomes US interest in preventing
further deterioration of the security situation in South Asia,''
said a Pakistan foreign ministry statement issued late Tuesday,
after Talbott's first round of talks with Pakistan's Foreign
Secretary Shamshad Ahmed.
	   More substantive talks were planned for Wednesday with Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif and Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub.
	   Slow progress was reported out of India where Talbott held two
days of talks with Indian officials.
	   ``Both sides are looking for areas of agreement,'' U.S. Embassy
spokeswoman in India, Kiki Munshi, told reporters Tuesday. ``This
is a process. It's not a one-shot thing. There is steady
movement.''
	   In India, a senior Foreign Ministry official said India will
propose a nuclear no-first-use agreement to Pakistan when the two
prime ministers meet next week.
	   Sharif and Atal Bihari Vajpayee of India will meet at a summit
of seven heads of state next week in Colombo, the Sri Lankan
capital.
	   The official, speaking on condition of anoynymity, said
discussions on an agreement not to use nuclear weapons first could
later be broadened to a regional level. He did not specifically
name China. India has said China's nuclear power was its primary
concern when it decided to go nuclear.
	   It will be their first meeting since the two countries conducted
nuclear tests in May, each declaring itself a nuclear weapons
state. The tests provoked international condemnation and economic
sanctions.
	   Vajpayee, elected just two months before authorizing the tests,
and Sharif also are expected to try to end a deadlock over resuming
high-level bilateral talks on the disputed territory of Kashmir,
that has been the cause of two wars between Pakistan and India.
	   During Talbott's talks with Ahmed, Pakistan pressed for world
involvement in settling the Kashmir dispute.
	   India has rejected international mediation in the Kashmir
dispute. Both countries lay claim to a united Kashmir, divided
between Pakistan and India by the departing British in 1947.
	   Most analysts expect Talbott to push Pakistan to sign the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty and possibly to roll back its nuclear
program.
	   Pakistan also has said it won't sign the test ban treaty that
would give an advantage to rival India.
	   Pakistan's fragile economy, which depends more heavily than
India's on international loans, has suffered from economic
sanctions the United States imposed on both countries after their
nuclear tests.
	   There is a possibility that Pakistan may seek a moratorium on
its debt repayment, Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz said earlier.
	   Foreign exchange reserves have fallen to dlrs 600 million,
nearing a record low.
	   In New Delhi, diplomats said Tuesday that other rich donor
nations that clamped anti-nuclear sanctions on India have no plans
to resume suspended aid.
	   The European Union's current chair, Austria, is to begin
discussions with India on behalf of the union to reassess political
and strategic developments, diplomatic sources said. But plans are
at such a tentative stage that no one would discuss details. 	   
</TEXT>
