<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Kuwait,0165 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraq says 1,000 still missing from Gulf War
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Baghdad said Tuesday that more than 1,000
Iraqis are still missing from the 1991 Gulf War and is calling on
foreign countries to pressure Kuwait to help account for them.
	   The National Assembly has sent messages to humanitarian
organizations and parliaments in Arab and other countries, calling
on them to press Kuwait, the official Iraqi News Agency reported.
	   The agency said Iraq believes many of the missing are still
detained by Kuwaiti authorities who should ``immediately reveal
their fate and return them to Iraq.''
	   There was no immediate comment from Kuwait.
	   Kuwait repeatedly has said that 600 people _ including more than
500 Kuwaitis, more than a dozen Saudis and other foreign nationals
_ are still unaccounted for since Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait,
which set off the Gulf War.
	   Iraq has repeatedly denied that it is holding any Kuwaitis in
its jails. 	   
</TEXT>
