<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Algeria, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Algeria says Red Cross will be allowed to visit prisons
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS for AMs with Red Cross, Algerian and Chanet comment. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo GEV108-109 &QL; 
 &UR; By PHILIP WALLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ A senior Red Cross official plans to go to Algeria
to discuss resuming visits to prisoners, the organization said
Tuesday, a day before U.N. diplomats are to arrive in Algeria for a
fact-finding tour.
	   Jean-Daniel Tauxe, director of operations for the International
Committee of the Red Cross, will travel to Algiers on a date to be
agreed with the Algerian authorities, an ICRC statement said. A
date in October has been proposed.
	   Discussions will focus on conditions and arrangements for the
resumption of visits. Following a disagreement over conditions,
Algeria asked the Red Cross to suspend prison visits and other
humanitarian operations in 1992.
	   The statement came after Algerian ambassador to Geneva,
Mohamed-Salah Dembri, told the U.N. committee reviewing adherence
to the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights that
Algeria was agreeable to allowing Red Cross officials back into its
prisons.
	   ``The program drawn up by the ICRC will include prison visits
and that doesn't perturb us in the least,'' Dembri said.
	   The organization demanded regular, private access to all
detainees and detention centers.
	   Since 1992, it has been carrying out regular missions to the
country from Tunisia, ICRC spokeswoman Beatrice Megevand said.
	   Members of the U.N. committee told an Algerian government
delegation it had not adequately addressed queries about widespread
massacres and other atrocities, and prison visits by the
International Red Cross.
	   ``What we are looking for are some answers,'' committee member
Thomas Buergenthal, of the United States, said.
	   Committee chairman Christine Chanet told reporters some of the
delegation's answers were ``a bit feeble.''
	   Dembri told committee members that they may have misinterpreted
the delegation's responses.
	   A six-member U.N. team led by former Portuguese President Mario
Soares is to fly to Algiers Wednesday.
	   The Washington-based group Human Rights Watch said in a press
statement Tuesday that the visit shouldn't be seen as a substitute
for more in-depth investigations by U.N. experts on torture and
extrajudicial executions.
	   Algeria has steadfastly rejected claims there is a serious human
rights crisis in the country. Instead, it insists the killings are
an internal affair and that terrorism is the major problem.
	   Some countries and international human rights groups have
suggested that the army or government-armed self-defense forces
might have had at least a passive role in some massacres.
	   The Algerian government has been fighting an Islamic insurgency
for the last six years in a conflict which has left at least 75,000
people dead.
 &UR; (pw)
</TEXT>
