<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Argentina-Menem-Re-Election,0335 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
President Menem renounces intention to seek third straight term
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By KEVIN GRAY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) _ In a surprise move, President
Carlos Menem on Tuesday renounced his intention to seek a third
straight term in next year's presidential race.
	   Menem told a press conference at the Olivos presidential palace
that he would ``definitely'' not seek another term as president,
adding ``I will leave power December 10'' of next year.
	   ``After a prolonged analysis, I have resolved to exclude myself
from whatever course of action to compete in 1999,'' Menem said,
flanked by his ministers, governors and other members of his
Peronist party.
	   ``I don't want anything or anybody to interfere with the
objective of making Argentina a country that's worth living in,''
he said.
	   In order to seek a third consecutive term, currently barred
under Argentina's 1994 constitution, Menem supporters had talked
for months of either seeking a constitutional amendment, or asking
the Supreme Court to declare the ban on a third term
unconstitutional.
	   Opposition leaders reacted skeptically to the president's
surprise announcment.
	   ``I don't believe one word he says,'' said Carlos Alvarez, a
leader of the left-leaning Frepaso party, one of two that make up
the Alliance opposition.
	   Menem's announcement brings to a close an issue that has gripped
Argentina for most of the year.
	   The months of Menem re-election talk had caused a rift in his
party, particularly with his rival for the presidential nomination,
Buenos Aires Governor Eduardo Duhalde, and stalled many of the
country's top legislative efforts, including tax and labor code
reforms.
	   ``This ends the the internal political fighting,'' said Antonio
Cafiero, a Peronist senator and top party official.
	   Menem had remained tight-lipped of his intentions, while
allowing aides to speak openly of holding referendums to
demonstrate his popular support. 	   
</TEXT>
