<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Afghanistan-Aid Workers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Expelled aid groups warn of epidemics in Kabul
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Afghanistan-Aid Workers, UN-Afghanistan &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN PHILLIPS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Aid groups expelled from the Afghan capital by the
Taliban religious militia warned Tuesday of the risk of epidemics,
and insisted they be allowed to resume work -- but on their own
conditions.
	   Thirty-eight international aid groups pulled out of Kabul
Monday, following a Taliban edict for them all to move into a
dilapidated dormitory on the outskirts of the capital, or leave the
country.
	   Representatives of six French groups held a news conference in
Paris, and said that Taliban troops turned up Monday, without
notification, at aid centers and workers' homes.
	   They said they were forced to leave immediately, and that the
centers were boarded up.
	   ``One million Afghans are now without humanitarian aid and the
consequences will be felt immediately,'' said Alain Boinet, of the
aid group Solidarites.
	   ``There are risks of epidemics, deaths, and people fleeing the
area en masse.''
	   Boinet said cholera was the main threat to the population,
especially in the summer season, and that there had already been
outbreaks in the north of the country.
	   Jacky Mamou, president of Doctors of the World, urged the
Taliban authorities ``to reflect well on what has happened and the
risks in coming weeks and months.''
	   ``We are completely open to a renewal of dialogue. But we want
direct dialogue,'' he said. ``We will not accept any constraints,
or anything other than total access.''
	   Most of the aid workers fled to neighboring Pakistan.
	   The United Nations and the Red Cross did not fall under the
Taliban edict, and say they have no immediate plans to withdraw
their staff from the Afghan capital.
	   The aid groups provided subsidized food, clean water, medicine
and clothes and were repairing neighborhoods heavily damaged by
civil war.
	   Among the international groups that pulled out were Save the
Children, Care International and Children in Crisis.
	   The French groups were Doctors Without Borders, Doctors of the
World, Action against Hunger, ACTED, Pharmacists Without Borders,
and Solidarites.
	   Two weeks ago, the Taliban ordered the aid groups to relocate to
dormitories once used by students of Kabul's technical schools. The
battered buildings have been empty since Islamic insurgents swept
Afghanistan's communists from power in 1992.
	   Aid workers refused to move, voicing security concerns and
saying they couldn't afford to refurbish the dormitories.
	   Relations between the Taliban army and international aid groups
have been strained since 1996 when the religious militia swept into
Kabul, and imposed its harsh version of Islamic law.
	   (ip-eg)
</TEXT>
