<SLUG> BC-Brazil-Mandela,0188 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mandela visits Brazil
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) _ South African President Nelson Mandela
signed trade agreements with Brazilian President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso on Tuesday, the second day of an official visit.
	   During an open-air lunch in the gardens of the Alvorada
presidential residence, Mandela and his newlywed Graca Machel were
treated to a show of Brazilian folklore.
	   Mandela and his wife arrived in the capital Brasilia, Monday
evening for a brief visit before heading to Argentina, where he
will attend the July 24 Mercosur Presidential Summit.
	   Mercosur is the customs union composed of Brazil, Argentina,
Uruguay and Paraguay.
	   In 1997 Brazil chalked up a dlrs 30 million surplus in its dlrs
700 million trade with South Africa. Brazil's chief exports to
South Africa are coffee, orange juice and soybeans. Its principal
imports from that country include diamonds, metals and gold.
	   Before leaving for Argentina on Wednesday, Mandela will visit
Congress. He may also meet with Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva, the
presidential candidate of the leftist Workers Party. 	   
</TEXT>
