w1036 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Economy 2ndLd-Writethru   07-21 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hailing IMF loan, Russian government promises real reforms
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMS. RECASTS, UPDATES thruout with new material, quotes,
analysis, CHANGES byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By ANNA DOLGOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The government vowed Tuesday to ignore resistance
from parliament and push ahead with an austerity program _ raising
hopes that a new international bailout may be the last one Russia
needs.
	   Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko said the government will impose
the economic reforms _ including spending cuts and tougher tax
collection _ by decree if necessary.
	   The reforms were demanded by the International Monetary Fund as
a condition for a new dlrs 11.2 billion loan approved Monday.
	   The first payment, expected to arrive later this week, will go
directly to the Central Bank and is intended largely to assure
investors and the markets that Russia can pay its bills and defend
its currency if necessary.
	   The loan _ part of a package expected to reach dlrs 17 billion
this year and next _ is the latest in a series Russia has received
since post-Soviet economic reforms began in 1992.
	   Past loans have been used to stall for time and temporarily prop
up Russian markets, while fundamental problems went unresolved.
	   Kiriyenko says he's committed to changing that.
	   ``What is important, both for the (International Monetary) Fund
and for ourselves, is ... balancing our expenses and revenues,''
Kiriyenko said, referring to the key problems of Russia's budget
deficit and abysmal tax collections.
	   ``The fund's loan is only one part of the (austerity) program,''
he said at a news conference. ``All the main things we have to do
ourselves, here in Russia.''
	   Kiriyenko's main stumbling block is the Communist-dominated
lower house of parliament, or the State Duma, which has
consistently blocked government reforms.
	   Former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin appeared eager to find
compromises with the Communist opposition in parliament and
demonstrated little aptitude for economic reform. However,
Kiriyenko _ a 35-year-old technocrat named premier in March _
appears less interested in compromises and more in pushing economic
reforms.
	   After parliament approved plans to raise only about one-third of
new revenues the government sought, Kiriyenko and President Boris
Yeltsin issued decrees last weekend raising property taxes and
import duties and expand a value-added tax to cover a wider range
of goods.
	   Kiriyenko said he was prepared to bypass parliament again to
push through the austerity program, which is a condition for the
IMF and other lenders.
	   ``I still hope that at least two main bills ... those on the
income tax and the land tax, and possibly several more minor ones _
will be reviewed and approved by the State Duma,'' he said. ``If
not, we will have to continue to act through government decrees and
orders.''
	   ``The failure to adopt bills ... forces even harsher measures,''
Kiriyenko said.
	   The government's deputy chief of staff, Sergei Vasilyev,
cautioned that the new loan was ``not a cure-all.''
	   ``It simply wins us time for deep economic changes and
structural reforms,'' he said at a separate news conference.
	   Russia's economy spent most of this decade in a painful
recession. It was showing its first signs of modest growth before
the latest financial crunch hit in the spring, triggered by a
combination of the Asian financial crisis, a fall in world oil and
gas prices and the government's budget deficit.
	   After months in a tailspin, the markets began recovering when
the IMF loan package was first announced last week. But stock
closed down again Tuesday, as investors raked in profits. The
Russian Trading System Index dipped 4.7 percent to close as 183.95
points from 193.02 Monday. The ruble weakened slightly against the
dollar.
	   (ad/ls/mr)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Russia-Economy, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
