<SLUG> BC-Tajikistan-UN, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0353 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Four U.N. employees die in Tajikistan, UN says shot and killed
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with details on location of attack, UN saying ambush,
names of victims. ADDS byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Four members of a U.N. observer mission to
Tajikistan were ambushed, shot and killed while patrolling the
north-central part of the country, U.N. officials said Tuesday. The
Security Council and U.N. chief condemned the attack.
	   The report differed from that of Tajik officials, who said the
observers died in an accident when their car plunged off a cliff in
the Pamir Mountains about 170 kilometers (100 miles) east of the
capital of the Central Asian country, Dushanbe.
	   The U.N. report came too late for Tajik officials to comment.
	   U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said information from U.N. officials
at the site confirmed the four had been shot and killed Monday
while on the road from Tavildara to Garm, about 90 miles east of
the capital. The four failed to report back to headquarters Monday
and were found Tuesday.
	   The U.N. special representative for Tajikistan, Jan Kubis,
recalled all field teams to Dushanbe and was in contact with the
president and opposition groups to ensure those responsible were
brought to justice, Eckhard said.
	   ``The members of the Security Council condemn this murder,''
council President Sergey Lavrov of Russia said after the council
was briefed on the situation.
	   Secretary-General Kofi Annan was ``deeply depressed'' about the
deaths and condemned them, Eckhard said. Annan repeated that
security of U.N. personnel rests with host countries.
	   The four killed were military observers Maj. Ryszard Szcwczyk of
Poland and Maj. Adolfo Sharpegue of Uruguay; civil affairs officer
Akino Yutaka of Japan and their Tajik translator, Jourajon
Mahramov.
	   About 70 U.N. observers are stationed in Tajikistan to monitor
provisions of a peace deal reached last year that ended the former
Soviet republic's civil war.
</TEXT>
