<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede JERUSALEM
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Netanyahu wants several issues discussed int talks &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: AMs RECAST. UPDATES throughout with Netanyahu comments, Israel
and Palestinians consulting with Egypt; Changes Byline &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By DAFNA LINZER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said
Tuesday he wanted Israeli-Palestinian negotiations over an American
peace proposal to include other issues besides a long overdue
Israeli troop withdrawal.
	   The Palestinians have said they agreed to enter the latest round
of direct talks with the understanding that only two issues _ the
scope of a West Bank troop withdrawal and the PLO covenant _ would
be on the agenda.
	   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat complained that no progress had
been made in the first 48 hours of talks with Israel. ``Until now,
nothing has come out of all the sessions that have been held,
nothing that can give any positive indication of improving their
(the Israelis') position,'' Arafat said.
	   Netanyahu however said he was determined to reach an agreement.
	   The direct negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians
began on Sunday at the urging of the United States, which has said
it has exhausted its role as a mediator.
	   The Palestinians have been attending the talks reluctantly,
setting a week's time limit and saying they would not accept any
changes in the U.S. proposal for a 13 percent pullback that was
first made in January.
	   But Netanyahu said in an interview with Israel TV that there
were more issues, such as the extradition of suspects and reduction
of the Palestinian police force, that he wanted discussed. ``There
are at least eight or nine other issues and I want specific answers
on all of them,'' he said.
	   ``When the Americans came out with their proposal ... it was
very specific about one thing only, the percentages of a withdrawal
which Israel is not willing to carry out in the next redeployment.
It wasn't clear what, if anything, would happen with the third
withdrawal. It wasn't clear or specific at all regarding the
obligations of the Palestinians, and we have advanced greatly on
these issues since then and we are trying to complete them,'' he
said.
	   In the first two sessions Sunday and Monday, Israel proposed
that only 10 percent of the land be handed over to full Palestinian
control, while the remaining 3 percent be declared a nature reserve
with a ban on construction.
	   ``We rejected the proposals,'' said Palestinian negotiator
Hassan Asfour. ``We are not here to negotiate with the Israelis. We
are here to hear from them a `yes' to the American initiative.''
	   Netanyahu referred to the proposal in an interview with Israel
TV as a ``bridging concept which came up between ourselves and the
United States some time ago,'' but would not elaborate on the
specifics.
	   Both Arafat and Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
consulted with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak Tuesday and Israel
radio reported that Israel asked Mubarak to pressure the
Palestinians to take a more flexible position on the process.
	   Negotiators from both sides were meeting at a kibbutz outside
Jerusalem for further talks Tuesday.
	   Despite the ongoing deadlock, far-right members of Netanyahu's
government, apparently concerned that the prime minister would
eventually agree to a 13 percent pullback, threatened to topple the
government.
	   Chief among those threatening to leave were Cabinet hawk Ariel
Sharon, considered most capable of leading a right-wing revolt, and
Agriculture Minister Rafael Eitan, leader of the far-right Tsomet
Party.
	   Eitan said he would quit the coalition if Netanyahu handed over
more than 7 percent of the West Bank.
	   Netanyahu's coalition has 61 legislators in the 120-seat
parliament. A departure of Tsomet, which has five lawmakers, would
rob Netanyahu of his parliamentary majority.
	   Netanyahu's critics have said he has been avoiding a decision on
a troop pullback for months _ even at the cost of alienating the
United States _ because he fears losing power.
 &UR; pvs-dl 	   
</TEXT>
