<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Italy Coach, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Maldini out as Italy coach
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: INSERTS Maldini's record as coach in new graf 7. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Italy's coaching carousel continues to spin, with
Cesare Maldini officially out as head of the national soccer team,
the federation announced Tuesday.
	   Maldini and federation president Luciano Nizzola met in Turin on
Saturday and agreed to the change. Nizzola will decide on a
successor ``in the coming days,'' a statement from his office said.
	   Newspaper reports Tuesday said Dino Zoff, former 'keeper and
captain of the Azzurri and now in Serie A club Lazio of Rome's
front office, will be hired as coach this week, the third person to
hold the post in 19 months.
	   A federation spokesman declined to comment.
	   Maldini, whose contract expires at the end of the year, has been
offered another position with the national soccer body.
	   Maldini took over from Arrigo Sacchi _ who was sent packing in
part because of a dismal 1996 European Championships _ in December
1996. Under Maldini, Italy scraped into the World Cup finals
through a two-game playoff and lost to eventual champion France in
the quarterfinals on penalty kicks.
	   During his tenure, the team had 11 wins, 7 draws and one loss _
2-0 to England in an exhibition match last year _ while scoring 30
goals and allowing 12.
	   He was widely criticized in Italy for relying on tactics that
were too defense-minded.
	   Maldini, on vacation in Tuscany, was tight-lipped.
	   ``Talk about the national soccer team? I don't need to issue
statements, so I will not talk about that matter,'' he told the
ANSA news agency hours before the official announcement was made in
Rome.
	   Zoff, also a candidate to replace Sacchi in 1996, captained
Italy to its last major triumph, the 1982 World Cup title. He
played in a record 112 games for the country.
	   He has had brief stints as coach of Lazio and Juventus of Turin
in Serie A.
	   (hjf/vls)
</TEXT>
