<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
After heavy fighting, U.S. diplomat meets Kosovo leader
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. UPDATES with U.S. diplomat meeting with Albanian leader
in Pristina, Serbian police releasing 250, handing over 12 bodies,
200 reported in prison; CHANGES byline, edits. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo PRI109
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia - After some of the heaviest fighting in
weeks, a senior U.S. envoy stepped up efforts Tuesday to cobble
together peace talks in Kosovo, admitting that progress has been
slow.
	   Albanian sources reported continued fighting near the strategic
central town of Orahovac.
	   The fighting around Orahovac has cast doubt on the possibility
of a negotiated settlement between Serbia, which dominates what
remains of Yugoslavia, and the independence-minded Albanians who
make up 90 percent of Kosovo's population.
	   Christopher Hill, the U.S. ambassador to Macedonia, who acts as
a go-between, met with Ibrahim Rugova, the moderate ethnic Albanian
leader, a day after he conferred with Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic in Belgrade.
	   While no details were available on Hill's talks with Milosevic,
Zoran Lilic, a top aide, said Yugoslavia was ready to offer the
highest level of autonomy to the Kosovo Albanians.
	   But he said Yugoslavia expects further efforts from all
international organizations and particularly from the United
States, which, he claimed, has a lot of influence on the Kosovo
Albanians.
	   Before meeting Rugova, Hill indicated that no quick solution to
the Kosovo crisis was in sight. Asked if progress had been made, he
said, ``That would be too strong but we are trying.''
	   ``There are a number of issues related to the political track we
are working on,'' he added without elaboration.
	   Rugova's main party, the Democratic League of Kosovo, on Tuesday
condemned what it called the ``violence and massacre by Serb forces
in Orahovac,'' which appeared largely under Serb control.
	   On Monday, Rugova declared that all Kosovo Albanian political
parties would unite ``in the next few days'' in a coalition
government. But it was unlikely the rebels would accept the
self-styled government's authority.
	   Earlier Tuesday, Serb police and ethnic Albanian rebels were
reported to have clashed near Orahovac for a fourth day.
	   Serb authorities escorted reporters to the southern edge of
Orahovac on Monday to see weapons captured from the Kosovo
Liberation Army, which launched a strong attack there Saturday.
	   But Serb escorts refused to allow reporters into the center of
town, saying Albanian snipers were still firing at police. In the
distance, smoke billowed from fires in the area, suggesting the
conflict there was not quite over.
	   On Tuesday, the Kosovo Information Center, which is close to
ethnic Albanian politicians, claimed Serb forces were still
shelling KLA positions in Orahovac on Tuesday and that fighting was
also raging in outlying villages.
	   The center said at least 36 Albanians had been killed, including
women and children. State radio in Tirana, Albania, reported
Tuesday evening that eleven dead were still lying in the streets.
	   Late Monday police brought 12 bodies to a morgue in Prizren, 75
kilometers (45 miles) south of Pristina, apparently people killed
in the fierce fighting around Orahovac, the center said.
	   It also reported that some 250 ethnic Albanians had been taken
to Prizren from Orahovac, many of them women and children, in the
past three days. Police started releasing them in groups on Tuesday
following interrogation.
	   But Albanian state radio said that of 200 Albanian men held in a
prison in Prizren, 20 were released on Tuesday, and one of them
reportedly said that those still in prison were in serious
condition.
	   Earlier in the day, the Albanians claimed about 100 ethnic
Albanians had been detained in a police crackdown in Prizren, but
it was not clear if they were part of the 200 or so prisoners.
	   And the Yugoslav news agency Tanjug said Albanian gunmen
attacked and lead and zinc mine 32 kilometers (20 miles) west of
Pristina late Monday but were driven off by security guards.
	   None of the reports could be independently confirmed.
	   House-to-house battles in Orahovac forced as many as 25,000
residents from the town and its surroundings to the KLA-controlled
town of Malisevo, 16 kilometers (10 miles) to the north, according
to local media reports.
	   Serb police say as many as 600 KLA rebels tried to seize the
town, capturing and shutting down a power plant before moving on to
the post office. The police forced them to flee by car or by foot,
leaving weapons behind.
	   (ih/jg/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
