w1055 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Canada-WarCrimes     07-21 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Canada-War Crimes,0445 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Canada escalates effort to expel suspected war criminals
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DAVID CRARY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TORONTO (AP) _ Criticized in the past for lax pursuit of war
criminals, Canada on Tuesday announced a five-fold increase in
funding to root out Nazi-linked suspects and immigrants accused of
modern-day war crimes.
	   The government said it will allocate dlrs 46.8 million (dlrs 31
million U.S.) over three years to strengthen efforts to bring war
criminals to justice.
	   The funds will enable the Justice Department to open new
investigations of World War II cases and allow the Immigration
Department to deport scores of people suspected of crimes in modern
conflicts. The two departments' war-crimes units will work together
more closely.
	   Jewish organizations have denounced Canada's past efforts to
track down Nazi war criminals. The new initiative appeared to be
part of a series of steps to rebut such charges.
	   ``Canada is not a safe haven for war criminals,'' Justice
Minister Anne McLellan said in announcing the funding.
	   Since 1987, the government has investigated 1,571 suspected war
criminals from World War II. Ninety cases are being actively
pursued, and deportation proceedings are under way in nine of the
cases.
	   About one-fourth of the new money will go toward dealing with
World War II cases. The rest goes to the Immigration Department to
help it rid Canada of an estimated 320 suspects from more recent
conflicts, ranging from Rwanda to the former Yugoslavia.
	   According to an Immigration Department report, members of death
squads, torturers and individuals accused of genocide have entered
Canada in recent years.
	   ``Let it be clear to war criminals and all those involved in
crimes against humanity who have fled to Canada that we are
determined to remove them from Canadian soil,'' said Immigration
Minister Lucienne Robillard.
	   Amendments to Canada's Extradition Act, introduced in Parliament
in May, are designed to ease extradition of suspected war criminals
for trial either in another country or before an international
tribunal.
	   In the 1980s and early 1990s, Canada made a few unsuccessful
attempts to prosecute suspected World War II war criminals.
Starting in 1995, the government shifted its strategy, seeking
instead to strip suspected war criminals of their citizenship and
deport them on grounds they concealed information about their past
when they entered Canada.
	   Of the 14 cases initiated since 1995, three suspects left the
country before deportation was ordered, two suspects died before
completion of their cases, and nine other cases are pending.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Canada-War Crimes; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
