<SLUG> BC-Slovakia-Floods, 1st Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Flash floods kill at least 23 people
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. UPDATDS with new death toll, estimates damage to roads,
railroad system, Roma village destroyed. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BRATISLAVA, Slovakia (AP) _ Heavy rains sent rivers and streams
over their banks in eastern Slovakia, killing at least 23 people,
including at least five children, police said Tuesday.
	   At least 20 other people were missing Tuesday following the
flash floods, which swept across a dozen villages, washing away
bridges, homes and roads, police reported.
	   Slovak radio also said about 3,500 people were forced to seek
shelter on higher ground.
	   According to the private Markiza TV station, some 1,000 rescue
workers were in action to help people affected by the flooding.
	   A government spokesman estimated that damage to state roads and
the railroad system surpassed 100 million Slovak crowns (dlrs 3
million).
	   A Roma village of 500, built by the Svinka river, was completely
destroyed by the floodwater. At least five children were killed
there.
	   In the neighboring Czech Republic, the CTK news agency quoted
policeman Elemir Cuprak as saying that 11 of the victims died in
the county of Sabinov, 360 kilometers (225 miles) northeast of
Bratislava.
	   Cuprak said the worst damage occurred in the country's biggest
Gypsy settlement near the Jarovnice village, where water destroyed
most of the houses. He said panic caused by the floods makes
assessment of death toll and damages in the settlement difficult.
	   A 2-year-old child drowned and two persons were missing near
Prerov, 400 kilometers (250 miles) northeast of Bratislava, CTK
said.
	   Slovak radio said the downpour began about 6:30 p.m. (1630 GMT)
Monday in northeastern Slovakia and that water levels in local
streams rose rapidly by up to six meters (yards), trapping victims.
	   (pvs/jd/rp)	   
</TEXT>
