<HEADLINE>
Developing countries helped to line up intellectual property laws
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ Developing countries will get help to bring their
laws on copyrights and other intellectual property into line with
an international accord by the Millennium, the World Trade
Organization said Tuesday.
	   The WTO and the World Intellectual Property Organization will
provide assistance to governments to prepare legislation, training
and institution-building, the two organizations said in a joint
statement.
	   The countries have until January 1, 2000 to conform to the WTO
Agreement on Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights.
	   The accord sets new international standards for laws on
copyright, patents, trademarks and other intellectual property
aimed at preventing piracy and counterfeit goods.
</TEXT>
