<SLUG> BC-Russia-Germany, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian, German defense ministers discuss Kosovo, other issues
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with new quotes, more details on talks. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The Russian and German defense ministers agreed
that a political solution is needed to end the crisis in the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo, a news agency reported Tuesday.
	   The two ministers held talks in the Black Sea resort of Sochi,
touching on Kosovo, defense technology cooperation and other
issues, the Interfax news agency said.
	   ``The Kosovo situation is developing extremely unfavorably,''
said Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev. ``It is most important
to get representatives of the conflicting sides to the negotiating
table through joint efforts.''
	   Russia and Germany have many similar views on Kosovo, although
Germany has ``its own accents,'' said German Defense Minister
Volker Ruehe. ``A political solution to the problem is needed.''
	   Sergeyev said tensions in Kosovo threaten peace and stability
throughout the Balkans. He said the Kosovo Liberation Army is
receiving reinforcements and that this jeopardizes attempts to
settle the conflict.
	   Ruehe noted that officials from Germany and Russia are working
on the development of a new An-70 cargo plane, and their
recommendations are expected by late September.
	   Russia and Germany plan joint paratrooper exercises next year,
he said.
	   (ls) 	   
</TEXT>
