<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-SKorea </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian security agency says dispute with South Korea over
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's Foreign Intelligence Service believes
that the recent spy dispute with South Korea is over, a spokesman
said Tuesday.
	   The dispute began July 4 when Russia ordered the expulsion of a
South Korean diplomat on espionage charges. His alleged Russian
contact was arrested for treason.
	   South Korea retaliated by expelling a Russian diplomat in Seoul.
	   The two countries then agreed to limit the number of
intelligence agents assigned to one another's diplomatic missions.
	   ``We exchanged blows, which was not too pleasant,'' said Yuri
Kobaldze, spokesman for the Foreign Intelligence Service.
	   ``But today, I think the two parties have calmed down and
realized that no spy scandals or expulsions should stand in the way
of the normal development of bilateral relations,'' he said,
according to the Interfax news agency.
	   The spy incident ``can be considered to be over,'' he said.
	   The dispute was the most serious between Russia and South Korea
since the former adversaries opened formal diplomatic relations in
1990. The former Soviet Union was a longtime ally of Seoul's rival,
communist North Korea.
	   (ls) 	   
</TEXT>
