<SLUG> BC-Romania-Unscheduled Landing </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
In-flight row with unruly passengers prompts unscheduled landing
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) _ An unruly passenger aboard a British
charter plane carrying vacationers to Turkey early Tuesday prompted
the pilot to make an unscheduled landing in Bucharest, airport
officials said.
	   No one apparently was hurt in the incident.
	   The man, identified in a report by the Meiafax news agency as
Michael Ian Williams, 26, caused a commotion on board the Boeing
757 belonging to Flying Colors, a private British company, by
violent behavior first toward his companion, then to flight
attendants.
	   Sorin Stoicescu, the Otopeni airport commander, read the pilot's
report saying the man became abusive and tried to enter the
cockpit. But the pilots locked the door. It was not clear how he
was restrained. Mediafax said Williams was unarmed.
	   The plane, which took off from Manchester, England, was bound
for Turkey. It proceeded on its journey some time after the
incident, the officials said.
	   Williams was held by Romanian border police in a room at
Bucharest's Otopeni airport, pending the arrival of consular
officials from the British Embassy.
	   He was subsequently declared deported and put on a Romanian
Tarom flight bound for London.
	   (buc/rp) 	   
