w1091 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Egypt-Violence     07-21 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Violence </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Militant adviser: Islam bans killing tourists, civilians
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ A study by the man considered to be the
religious adviser to Egypt's most violent militant group says that
Islam bans killing tourists and civilians.
	   Ninety-six foreigners and hundreds of civilians have been killed
in attacks since extremists began a violent campaign in 1992 to
overthrow the secular government of President Hosni Mubarak and
install strict religious rule.
	   It was not clear if the study by Mohammed Mokhtar Mustafa would
have a significant impact on the militant movement, which has
appeared fractured in the wake of a government crackdown.
	   Muntasser el-Zayyat, a lawyer close to the insurgents, said
Mustafa is a senior member of a board of six men who lead al-Gamaa
al-Islamiya or the Islamic Group.
	   ``A non-fighting civilian, who is not involved in the least in
the actions of war or battle, is not to be targeted with death,''
Mustafa wrote in the introduction to a nearly 500-page book
entitled ``The Ruling on Killing Civilians in Islamic Law.'' Parts
of the study were obtained by The Associated Press Tuesday.
	   The study was written in London in late 1997 and is not expected
to be released in Egypt.
	   Mustafa, who lives in London, was not available for comment. He
was imprisoned in Egypt for seven years for taking part in the 1981
assassination of President Anwar Sadat.
	   ``Religious duty, injustice and the suppression our people face
are the causes which drove some Islamic groups to do what they
did,'' Mustafa wrote.
	   ``But while these causes justify allowing Islamic groups to
oppose their regimes, their Jihad (holy war) must abide by the
rules of Shariah (Islamic law).''
	   Six members of al-Gamaa al-Islamiya murdered 58 tourists and
four Egyptians in a November attack on a Pharaonic temple in
southern Egypt.
	   The attack, which devastated Egypt's vital tourism industry,
shocked some of the group's leaders living in exile in Europe.
	   They called for a cease-fire in Egypt.
	   Rifai Taha, an exiled hard-liner believed to be al-Gamaa's
mastermind, said the group would target Egypt's tourism industry,
but not tourists.
	   More than 1,200 people, mostly police and militants, have been
killed in the insurgents' six-year violent campaign.
	   El-Zayyat has offered to mediate between militant leaders and
government officials, but the government has said it will not deal
with people it considers criminals.
 &UR; ms-tt-lm 	   
</TEXT>
