w1094 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 2ndLd   07-21 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld,0519 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serb police claim victory over KLA in strategic town
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in top 15 grafs with U.S. diplomat meeting with
Albanian leader in Pristina, Serbian police releasing 250, handing
over 12 bodies, 200 reported in prison. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo PRI109 &QL; 
 &UR; By ANNE THOMPSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Serb police and ethnic Albanian
rebels reportedly clashed near a strategic town in central Kosovo
for a fourth day Tuesday, and Albanian sources claimed at least 36
Albanians had been killed.
	   Meanwhile, a senior U.S. envoy stepped up efforts Tuesday to
cobble together peace talks in Kosovo, admitting that progress has
been slow.
	   Serb authorities escorted reporters to the southern edge of
Orahovac on Monday to see weapons captured from the Kosovo
Liberation Army, which launched a strong attack there Saturday.
	   Serb escorts refused to allow reporters into the center of town,
saying Albanian snipers were still firing at police. In the
distance, smoke billowed from fires in the area.
	   The Kosovo Information Center, which is close to ethnic Albanian
politicians, claimed Serb forces were still shelling KLA positions
in Orahovac and that fighting was also raging in outlying villages.
	   The center said at least 36 Albanians had been killed, including
women and children.
	   The fighting cast doubt on the possibility of a negotiated
settlement between Serbia, which dominates what remains of
Yugoslavia, and the independence-minded Albanians who make up 90
percent of Kosovo's population.
	   U.S. envoy Christopher Hill met with Ibrahim Rugova, the
moderate ethnic Albanian leader, a day after he conferred with
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic in Belgrade.
	   No details on Hill's talks with Milosevic were available. When
asked before meeting Rugova if progress had been made, Hill said,
``That would be too strong but we are trying.''
	   Rugova's main party, the Democratic League of Kosovo, on Tuesday
condemned what it called the ``violence and massacre by Serb forces
in Orahovac,'' which appeared largely under Serb control.
	   Elsewhere, the Albanians claimed about 100 ethnic Albanians had
been detained in a police crackdown in Prizren, southwest of the
capital, Pristina.
	   The Yugoslav news agency Tanjug said Albanian gunmen attacked a
lead and zinc mine 32 kilometers (20 miles) west of Pristina late
Monday but were driven off by security guards.
	   Late Monday police brought 12 bodies to a morgue in Prizren, 75
kilometers (45 miles) south of Pristina, apparently people killed
in the fierce fighting around Orahovac, the center said.
	   It also reported that some 250 ethnic Albanians had been taken
to Prizren from Orahovac, many of them women and children, in the
past three days. Police started releasing them in groups on Tuesday
following interrogation.
	   But Albanian state radio said that of 200 Albanian men held in a
prison in Prizren, 20 were released on Tuesday, and one of them
reportedly said that those still in prison were in serious
condition.
	   None of, graf 8 pvs
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld; CT:i; 
