<SLUG> BC-Canada-GM-Pickup Plant,0207 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM's Canada truck plant to be shut down by Wednesday
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With US-GM-Strike, Mexico-GM &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   OSHAWA, Ontario (AP) _ Production at the last General Motors
plant still operating in Canada will be shut down Wednesday,
disrupting work on a new pickup truck, company and union officials
said.
	   The shutdown of the Oshawa truck plant is due to a shortage of
parts caused by two GM strikes in Michigan.
	   The plant is the lead assembly site for GM's new GMC Sierra and
Chevy Silverado pickup, a redesigned version of the company's
best-selling vehicle.
	   Company spokesman Greg Gibson said the parts shortage was
halting the final stages of production Tuesday afternoon. He said
work on preliminary stages would continue into the night, and the
entire assembly line was expected to stop early Wednesday.
	   About 3,800 people work at the truck plant. By Wednesday, 3,000
are expected to be laid off, while the others will be working on
non-production tasks.
	   GM had stockpiled parts to keep the Oshawa plant operating on a
reduced scale as technicians worked out the bugs prior to
full-scale production of the 1999 models. The new trucks were
supposed to start arriving in showrooms in September.
</TEXT>
