<HEADLINE>
Report: Two Russian journalists kidnapped in Kosovo
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Two Russian journalists were taken hostage and
held for several hours in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo, a news
agency reported Tuesday.
	   Ethnic Albanian gunmen stopped a car carrying TV reporters Oleg
Safiulin and Oleg Galanov late Monday, forced them out of the car,
blindfolded them and escorted them to a nearby house, ITAR-Tass
said in a report from the Yugoslav capital, Belgrade.
	   After a several hours' interrogation, the journalists were
released, although their interpreter was still being held, the news
agency said, quoting Russian diplomats in Yugoslavia.
	   A reporter for the Russian newspaper Izvestia, Sergei Mitin, was
beaten by gunmen from the Kosovo Liberation Army on Friday,
ITAR-Tass said. The gunmen also seized Mitin's car.
	   ``Regrettably, Russian journalists heading for Kosovo do not
fully understand that the area is a high risk zone,'' an
unidentified Russian diplomat was quoted as telling ITAR-Tass.
