<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Macedonia-Explosions, 2nd Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Three explosions shake Macedonia
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with new details, Solana visit, U.N. increases mission
in Macedonia &QL; 
 &UR; By KONSTANTIN TESTORIDES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) _ Three strong explosions shook the
Macedonian capital and two locations near the Yugoslav border early
Tuesday, a day before the scheduled visit by NATO's top civilian
official to this Balkan country.
	   No group claimed responsibility for the blasts, which all
occurred around 3 a.m. (0100 gmt). They caused considerable damage
but no injuries.
	   But the blasts raised fears of unrest in Macedonia, which
borders Yugoslavia's volatile Kosovo province, where the majority
ethnic Albanians are seeking secession from Serbia, the dominant
republic in Yugoslavia.
	   The Kosovo Liberation Army, which is fighting for independence
for Kosovo, claimed responsibility for a series of explosions in
January in Kumanovo and two other Macedonian towns populated by
ethnic Albanians.
	   There are fears that Kosovo fighting could spill over to
Macedonia. NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana is due in Macedonia
on Wednesday to discuss the Kosovo crisis with Macedonian
officials.
	   Fears of a broader Balkan conflict also prompted the United
Nations Security Council Tuesday to add about 300 troops to the
750-strong U.N. peacekeeping force already in Macedonia. The
council also agreed to extend the force's mandate until Feb. 28.
	   The majority of the new troops, 230, would be deployed at nine
new observation posts along the Kosovo and Albanian borders. In
addition, a reserve group of about 60 soldiers in two platoons
would patrol the ground and air.
	   The blast in the capital Skopje shattered windows at a downtown
publishing company and was so intense that it woke up residents
several kilometers (miles) from the scene.
	   ``The explosion was very strong, it woke us up and we all came
down to see what was going on,'' said Jovica Andjelkovic, a
37-year-old Skopje resident.
	   Later state radio reported that the second blast occurred in
front of the Macedonian army barracks in Kumanovo, 45 kilometers
(28 miles) north of Skopje. .
	   The third explosion a short time later damaged a locomotive of a
train passing through Tabanovci, along the border with Serbia,
about 2 kilometers (1.3 miles) north of Kumanovo. The state radio
said that the railway traffic was halted for several hours.
	   Macedonian government has recently reported a number of
incidents involving arms smuggling for ethnic Albanian fighters in
Kosovo, but has repeatedly denied that the KLA is active in the
former Yugoslav republic.
	   Late Monday, however, Macedonian Defense Minister Lazar
Kitanovski announced he was sending more troops to the borders to
prevent KLA groups from using the country to smuggle weapons to
fighters into Kosovo.
	   (pvs/str/jg/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
