w1111 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yemen-MinistersAttack 2ndLd-Writethru   07-21 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Ministers Attacked, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yemen tribesmen ambush ministers' convoy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Interior Ministry confirming attack

<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ Armed tribesmen on Tuesday opened fire at a
convoy carrying Yemen's interior minister and other high-ranking
officials, but all survived, the Interior Ministry said.
	   One of the officials, Gov. Naji al-Dhulaimi of al-Jawf province,
was injured in the right shoulder, the ministry said in a
statement. It did not give other details.
	   A police official said earlier Tuesday that al-Dhulaimi was
flown by helicopter to a military hospital in San`a, the capital,
along with six injured security guards.
	   Three of the guards suffered serious wounds, said the official,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   The ambush was carried out by a few tribes together to protest
against a recent 40 percent government hike in fuel prices, a
tribal leader said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
	   Interior Minister Hussein Mohammed Arab and Local Administration
Minister Sadek Amin Abu Ras, who escaped unhurt, returned to San`a
aboard the helicopter that ferried the injured.
	   The head of the national security organization, Ghaleb al-Qams,
was among those in the convoy, which was attacked in the hills that
straddle the provinces of al-Jawf and Marib. The oil rich region is
170 kilometers (105 miles) northeast of San`a.
	   The attackers hid behind rocks in the mountainous terrain and
began shooting as soon as the convoy of eight cars appeared, said
the tribal leader.
	   The ministers had arrived in the region earlier Tuesday to
review government troops.
	   The troops were sent to quell unrest which started June 19 when
the government raised the prices of gasoline, kerosene and cooking
gas to meet International Monetary Fund demands to remove
subsidies.
	   Security forces cordoned off the area after the ambush and
helicopter gunships hovered in search of the attackers, witnesses
said.
	   In its drive for financial reform, the government has already
cut other subsidies and stepped up privatization of
state-controlled companies.
	   An official death toll from the clashes has not been released,
but the Yemen Times newspaper said earlier this month that 52
people have been killed and 214 injured.
	   Tribesmen also have blown up seven pipelines in the area.
	   Large parts of Yemen are lawless, inhabited by tribes who do not
hesitate to use firearms in settling scores with rivals or to
express discontent with the government.
 &UR; str-fsa/vj-lm 	   
</TEXT>
