<SLUG> BC-Spain-Forest Blaze, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Four-day fire torches 26,000 hectares in northeast Spain
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with 26,000 hectares charred, sted 22,000;
Firefighters optimism &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BARCELONA, Spain, (AP) _ Firefighters were optimistic Tuesday
that a four-day blaze that has charred 26,000 hectares (64,250
acres) of forest and crop land in Spain's northeastern Catalonia
region would be under total control within 24 hours.
	   Two thirds of the land affected was forest while the remainder
was scrubland and crops, mostly cereals, a regional fire department
spokesman said.
	   ``The flames are out but there are still burning embers that
could rekindle the fires if we are not very careful,'' Carlos
Fernandez said.
	   Reduced temperatures, wind changes and a more humid atmosphere
had aided the firefighters, although earlier forecasts of overnight
showers had been revised, Fernandez said.
	   Temperatures in much of Spain have reached 38 degrees Celsius
(100 Fahrenheit) on a daily basis for over a week, quickening the
spread of Catalonia's worst fire for four years.
	   The four-day-old blaze, centering around an area 100 kilometers
(60-miles) northwest of Barcelona, has forced the evacuation of
some 600 vacationers from campsites, country houses and holiday
complexes. There were no fresh reports of evacuations Tuesday.
	   Some 2,000 people, including firefighters, police and volunteers
joined the battle to extinguish the fire that started Saturday from
causes yet to be established.
	   (cg/krt/jt)
</TEXT>
