w1125 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-HealthChief 3rdLd-Writethru   07-21 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Health Chief, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Brundtland shakes up WHO top team on first day
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with U.S. health secretary reaction in 12th, 13th
grafs. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos GEV101-106 &QL; 
 &UR; By GEIR MOULSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ New U.N. health chief Gro Harlem Brundtland on
Tuesday started her promised revamp of the World Health
Organization by naming a much-changed top team.
	   The former Norwegian prime minister pledged that ``we will not
be losing time'' in implementing new programs to combat smoking
among young people and malaria. She promised ``urgent attention''
to the fight against AIDS.
	   A packed hall of WHO staff watched as Brundtland named her new
``Cabinet.'' Hundreds more apparently anxious workers silently
followed her speech in the corridors outside.
	   ``What we do here in Geneva and in the regional offices matters
very little if it does not lead to a difference on the ground,''
Brundtland said.
	   The 50-year-old WHO has faced criticism for being preoccupied
with internal problems and lack of focus. Outgoing Director-General
Hiroshi Nakajima, of Japan, was accused by opponents of bad
management and being a poor communicator.
	   At Brundtland's request, many senior managers ``made available
their posts.''
	   In their place, she named a team with members from all the WHO's
six regions. There are six women among the nine new senior
managers.
	   Germany's Michael Scholtz was recruited from pharmaceutical firm
SmithKline Beecham to take charge of the WHO's health technology
and drugs division.
	   ``We need the experience and the knowledge that is there in
private industry,'' Brundtland told a news conference later,
although stressing that WHO must be ``people-friendly.''
	   She stressed that raising funds for the agency must be a
priority.
	   Former Tunisian health minister Souad Lyagoubi-Ouahchi and U.S.
communicable diseases expert David Heymann, already with WHO, were
among other team members.
	   Brundtland's ``management skill and her dedication to the cause
of global health are already making a mark,'' said Donna Shalala,
U.S. Secretary of Health and Human Services.
	   Shalala praised Brundtland's determination to combat smoking.
	   ``This is a serious sweep,'' said Daniel Warner, a specialist in
international organizations at the Graduate Institute of
International Studies in Geneva, calling the shakeup ``long
overdue.''
	   In New York, the Rockefeller Foundation announced a dlrs 2.5
million grant for Brundtland to recruit outside health experts for
the WHO.
	   Brundtland also announced a new code of conduct requiring senior
officials to disclose private sector interests such as
shareholdings and directorships, to send a ``clear message of high
standards.''
	   She is the third woman to take up a major U.N. post in the space
of a year, following human rights chief Mary Robinson and deputy
director-general Louise Frechette.
	   Brundtland was nominated as the health agency's director-general
in January. Her appointment was confirmed in May by its annual
assembly.
	   WHO organizes massive vaccination efforts, coordinates global
response to epidemics and fosters the widespread distribution of
medicines. It has more than 3,500 staff worldwide, some 1,300 of
them based in Geneva.
 &UR; (gm)	   
</TEXT>
