<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Brazil-Steel,0235 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mexico's Imsa, Brazil's CSN set up joint venture
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) _ Mexican conglomerate Grupo Imsa said
Tuesday it agreed to form a dlrs 300 million joint venture with
Brazil's Companhia Siderurgica Nacional.
	   The new company, CSN-Imsa Acos Revestidos SA, will manufacture
and distribute processed steel for construction and home appliance
industries in southern Brazil, Imsa said in a press release.
	   Operations are scheduled to begin in the third quarter of the
year 2000, with annual capacity estimated at 450,000 metric tons
(500,000 US tons).
	   CSN will have a 51 percent stake in the venture and Imsa 49
percent. The location of the manufacturing facility had not been
determined but was expected to be either in the Brazilian state of
Santa Catarina or the state of Parana, the company said.
	   CSN-Imsa Acos Revestidos will have capacity to produce 110,000
metric tons (120,000 US tons) of cold, rolled steel; 200,000
(220,000 US tons) of galvanized and galvalume steel, and 140,000
(155,000 US tons) of pre-painted steel.
	   Grupo Imsa's steel division, Imsa Acero, is the largest producer
of galvanized, galvalume and prepainted steel in Latin America.
	   CSN, based in the state of Rio de Janeiro, is the largest
integrated steel producer in Latin America with a total annual
capacity of 5.1 million metric tons of molten steel.
</TEXT>
