<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cyprus-EU, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU envoy in Cyprus, Turkish Cypriots refuse meeting
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with EU envoy addressing Turkish businessmen &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos NIC-101-2 Available
 &UR; By ALEX EFTY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) - European Union envoy David Hannay met
Tuesday with President Glafcos Clerides to discuss stalled peace
talks.
	   Hannay did not meet with Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash,
who has refused to hold talks with the EU envoy. Denktash is
insisting that the international community first recognize his
breakaway state and that the EU end its discussions on admitting
Cyprus.
	   Tensions have been rising on the island following Turkish
warnings that it will prevent any Cypriot deployment of Russian
anti-aircraft missiles. Greece has warned that it will aid Cyprus
if Turkey takes military action.
	   Hannay said his talks with Clerides, the Greek Cypriot leader,
centered on peace talks ``and the increase in tensions in recent
weeks.''
	   Talks between Clerides and Denktash stalled in August when
Denktash first demanded recognition for his breakaway state and
that the EU end its talks with Cyprus.
	   Hannay criticized Denktash in his Monday arrival statement,
saying that the Turkish Cypriot leader ``prefers isolation to
dialogue and this is a pity.''
	   ``I have not known any international problem that has been
helped to be solved by not talking about it,'' he said.
	   Hannay addressed Turkish Cypriot businessmen Tuesday and urged
them to drop objections to Cyprus' entry into the EU.
	   ``Turkish Cypriots would be equal partners in Cyprus' EU
membership, getting a say in the development of EU's future,'' he
said.
	   Cyprus has been divided since a 1974 Turkish invasion sparked by
an abortive coup by supporters of union with Greece. A breakaway
Turkish Cypriot state in the north is recognized only by Turkey,
which maintains 35,000 troops on the island.
