<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru,0542 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Council condemns NGO expulsion from Kabul
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: NEW throughout to UPDATE with council condemning Taliban move,
UN pledging to stay.
 &UR; With BC-Afghanistan-Aid Workers
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The Security Council on Tuesday condemned
the forced withdrawal of international aid organizations from the
Afghan capital and said it supported U.N. efforts to maintain
relief operations in their absence.
	   The council also repeated its condemnation of the Taliban's
``continued abuse of rights of women and girls, particularly in the
areas of health and education,'' said council President Sergey
Lavrov of Russia.
	   Lavrov's comments underscored the strained relations between the
United Nations and the Taliban religious leaders, who have imposed
a strict version of Islam in the 85 percent of Afghanistan they
control. But they also demonstrated the delicacy of the U.N. role
in the country.
	   Last week, the U.N. envoy to Afghanistan warned that patience
was running out with the Taliban and that the world body was coming
under pressure from donors to simply withdraw its 60 international
workers from the country.
	   But the U.N. humanitarian aid coordinator, Sergio Vieira de
Mello, has pledged to stay in Kabul and Afghanistan as a whole
despite the problems, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said Tuesday.
	   The United Nations didn't fall under the latest Taliban edict,
which forced about 200 aid workers from 38 international aid
organizations to pull out of Kabul on Monday rather than move into
war-damaged student dormitories. The aid workers said they feared
for their safety at the dormitories, and didn't have the money to
make extensive repairs.
	   United Nations and the Red Cross, which also didn't fall under
the edict, would maintain their programs in Kabul using existing
resources, local staff and Afghan-based aid groups, Eckhard said.
	   Nevertheless, the absence of the international non-governmental
organizations, which implemented U.N. aid programs, and the
freezing of EU funds for new projects, ``will have a detrimental
effect on 400,000 people in Kabul who have depended directly on NGO
assistance programs for food, medicines and basic services,'' he
said.
	   To try to stave off the immediate effects, one expelled group,
Save the Children, delivered a month's supply of anti-diarrheal and
anti-cholera drugs to local hospitals, program manager Kurt Tjossem
said in a phone interview after crossing the border into Pakistan.
	   A prolonged pullout, he said, ``could be a devastating lesson to
be learned,'' by the Taliban, he said.
	   The 15-member Security Council ``condemned the measures taken
recently by the Taliban authorities which make it impossible for
most NGOs to continue their work in Kabul, which in turn hinders
the delivery of humanitarian assistance to the population of the
city,'' Lavrov said.
	   The council expressed their support of U.N. relief programs that
are continuing, Lavrov said in comments to reporters after the
council was briefed on the situation by de Mello.
	   The council also condemned the death Monday of two U.N.
employees in the eastern city of Jalalabad, Lavrov said.
</TEXT>
