<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Parties </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former presidential candidate declares new Nigerian party
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ A former presidential candidate Tuesday
declared the founding of a new political party, the first since
Nigeria's military ruler announced his transition to democracy
program.
	   Tunji Braithwaite said the primary concern of the newly formed
Democratic Advanced Movement would be to ensure that the rule of
law is upheld in Nigeria, a country where human rights and
political freedoms have often been prime targets of military
dictators. It would also push for better housing and improved
public schools, he said.
	   Braithwaite withdrew as a possible presidential contender for
the Grassroots Democratic Movement earlier this year, saying the
process was rigged in favor of the country's late dictator, Gen.
Sani Abacha.
	   Eventually, all five state-sanctioned parties, including the
Grassroots Democratic Movement, nominated Abacha for elections
initially slated for August.
	   On Monday, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar announced presidential
elections for early next year and promised a return to civilian
government in May 1999. He said any Nigerians were free to form
political parties.
	   Among other things, he also dissolved the five
government-sanctioned parties and canceled the results of elections
conducted during the Abacha years.
	   On Tuesday, government officials took over the head offices of
the five parties in the capital of Abuja, under the watch of armed
anti-riot police. No disruptions were reported.
	   Senior civil servants have been named to administer the offices
and watch over their assets, which have been confiscated by the
government.
	   Abacha's five-year dictatorship was marked by an abysmal human
rights record, corruption and neglect. He died early in June of a
heart attack.
	   (fa-tjs)
</TEXT>
