<HEADLINE>
Olympics chief decries Tour de France drugs scandal
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Sports-Cycling-Tour de France-Doping &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   FLORENCE, Italy (AP) _ Olympics chief Juan Antonio Samaranch
decried the doping scandal that has hit the Tour de France and
lauded race officials Tuesday for expelling the Festina team.
	   ``We want to fight the doping problem. The International Olympic
Committee's position is clear and we support the various
organizations fighting this problem,'' Samaranch said in Florence,
where he attended the opening game of the World Baseball
Championships.
	   ``We must condemn what has happened at the Tour de France and we
support the decisions taken by the Tour organizers,'' the IOC
president said.
	   The Festina cycling team, including top rider Richard Virenque,
was kicked out of the Tour de France Friday after the team's
director admitted the team had supplied banned substances with
medical supervision to improve performances.
	   The scandal widened Tuesday, with a Festina doctor saying his
riders were ordered by their manager to pay for
performance-enhancing drugs. In addition, it was reported that
customs officials found the banned drug EPO in a car of officials
from the Dutch team TVM in March.
	   (hjf)
