<SLUG> BC-Macedonia-Explosions, 2nd Ld,0295 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Three explosions shake Macedonia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with new details, Solana visit, U.N. increases mission
in Macedonia. EDITS to conform. &QL; 
 &UR; By KONSTANTIN TESTORIDES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) _ Three strong explosions _ nearly
simultaneous _ shook the Macedonian capital and two locations near
the Yugoslav border early Tuesday, a day before the scheduled visit
by NATO's top civilian official to this Balkan country.
	   The explosions, which caused considerable damage but no
injuries, raised fears of unrest in Macedonia, which borders
Yugoslavia's volatile Kosovo province, where the majority ethnic
Albanians are seeking secession from Serbia, the dominant republic
in Yugoslavia.
	   No group claimed responsibility for the blasts, which occurred
around 3 a.m. (0100 gmt). But the Kosovo Liberation Army, which is
fighting for independence for the Serbian province of Kosovo, had
claimed responsibility for a series of explosions in January in
Kumanovo and two other Macedonian towns populated by ethnic
Albanians.
	   Fears of a broader Balkan conflict also prompted the U.N.
Security Council on Tuesday to add about 300 troops to the
750-strong U.N. peacekeeping force already in Macedonia. The
council also agreed to extend the force's mandate until Feb. 28.
	   The majority of the new troops, 230, would be deployed at nine
new observation posts along the Kosovo and Albanian borders. In
addition, a reserve group of about 60 soldiers in two platoons
would patrol the ground and air.
	   One of Tuesday's blasts shattered windows at a downtown
publishing company in the capital, Skopje, and woke up residents
several kilometers (miles) from the scene.
	   A high, graf 6 pvs
