<SLUG> BC-Mexico-GM, 1st Ld-Writethru,0269 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede MONTERREY
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; GM to resume production at Mexican plant next week &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with GM reopening its Silao plant. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ General Motors Corp. said it will resume
production Monday at its Silao assembly plant in central Mexico,
ending a stoppage caused by the United Auto Workers strike in the
U.S.
	   In a news release Tuesday, General Motors de Mexico SA said
engine production would remain suspended indefinitely at its Ramos
Arizpe plant in the northern Mexican state of Coahuila, idling
2,091 workers. Ramos Arizpe's vehicle assembly operations were
unaffected.
	   The Silao plant, which makes Silverado and Suburbans, was closed
June 23 by a parts shortage. All three GM plants in Mexico were
closed July 6 for an annual two-week maintenance break.
	   GM said parts from alternative suppliers enabled it to reopen
the Silao plant.
	   ``The company will continue to evaluate weekly its ability to
maintain production at levels that parts inventories will allow,''
GM de Mexico said. ``The objective of GM de Mexico is to minimize
the effects of the strike in the United States on our workers,
suppliers, dealerships and communities where we operate.''
	   GM said Monday it began assembling pickups this week at the
Ramos Arizpe plant, where it also produces Cavaliers, Chevys, Chevy
Monzas and Sunfires.
	   It said its engine plant in the central Mexican state of Mexico
continued to operate normally.
	   GM's three Mexican plants employ 9,389 people. Its 2,255
employees at Silao were scheduled to return to work Friday.
</TEXT>
