<HEADLINE>
British Virgin Islands ease restrictions on U.S. horses
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) _ The British Virgin
Islands will ease restrictions for race horses from the neighboring
U.S. Virgin Islands under an agreement signed Monday.
	   Previously, U.S. horses had to be put in quarantine for two
weeks before being allowed to compete at the Little A Racetrack on
the island of Tortola. The agreement eliminates the requirement.
	   British officials said they are considering a similar agreement
with Puerto Rico, another U.S. territory.
	   The changes come as the British Virgin Islands prepares for its
annual August Monday Festival race on Aug. 3.
	   The Little A Racetrack has just undergone a three year, dlrs 2
million renovation.
