<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Northern Ireland, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Man charged with murder in arson killing of three brothers
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in penultimate graf with comment from government
minister re apparent mortar attack graf 12 &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo XLD101 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ A 23-year-old man appeared in
court Tuesday on charges of murdering three young brothers in a
firebomb attack during a week of sectarian violence set off when
Protestant marchers were stopped from parading through a hostile
Catholic neighborhood.
	   Thomas Robert Garfield Gilmour of Ballymoney denied the charges,
police said during a hearing in Belfast Magistrates Court. Gilmour
had no criminal record and denied being a member of any
paramilitary organization, police said.
	   The Quinn brothers _ Richard, 11, Mark, 10, and Jason 9 _ were
killed in a July 12 arson attack on their home in Ballymoney, 40
miles (65 kms) northwest of Belfast.
	   A number of other people are being held for questioning in the
case, but police declined Tuesday to give a specific number.
	   Gilmour was ordered to be jailed pending a further court
appearance on Aug. 12.
	   Police believe the family was targeted because the boy's mother,
29-year-old Chrissie Quinn, was a Catholic who lived with a
Protestant boyfriend.
	   The attack was the worst incident of violence which followed a
violent standoff between Protestant marchers and security forces
blocking them from parading through a Catholic neighborhood in
Portadown, 25 miles (40 kms) southwest of Belfast.
	   Stunned by the killings, some leaders of the Orange Order called
for an end to the confrontation between its marchers and security
forces. The numbers of protesters camped near the Drumcree Anglican
church has dwindled to a token presence.
	   In Newry, 35 miles (55 km) south of Belfast, an explosion in a
police station parking lot late Tuesday afternoon _ apparently
caused by a mortar shell _ caused no injuries.
	   Police, who believed the device was fired from the back of a
van, called in a bomb disposal team to examine an object lying in
the parking area at Corry Square station.
	   There was no indication of who was responsible. But mortars were
a weapon used by the Irish Republican Army, so suspicion fell on
dissidents who oppose the present cease-fire and the participation
of the IRA-allied Sinn Fein party in Northern Ireland's new
Assembly.
	   Government minister Paul Murphy described the attack as ``a
cold-blooded and utterly despicable attempt to murder members of
the security forces,'' and said that those responsible ``showed a
clear and callous contempt for the safety of the people of Newry.''
	   Police and soldiers were inside the base at the time of the
attack, a Royal Ulster Constabulary spokeswoman said, but no one
was reported hurt.
	   (rb-scl-rs)
</TEXT>
