<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Tainted Blood </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Commission accuses ministers of protectionism in AIDS test
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NICOLAS MARMIE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ The investigative commission of a special court
accused former Prime Minister Laurent Fabius and two of his Cabinet
members of contributing to France's AIDS-tainted blood scandal by
trying to keep an American AIDS test off the market, The Associated
Press learned Tuesday.
	   Fabius, former Social Affairs Minister Georgina Dufoix and
former Health Minister Edmond Herve were ordered on Friday to stand
trial for involuntary homicide in connection with their roles in
the scandal in the mid-1980s.
	   The charges carry a maximum penalty of five years in prison and
a total of dlrs 130,000 in fines.
	   All three claim they never knowingly approved the use of
contaminated blood in transfusions. They served from 1984-86 in the
Socialist government under President Francois Mitterrand.
	   The trial before the special Court of Justice of the Republic,
which will climax a six-year saga that shook France's public health
system, will likely not be heard before next year, according to
judicial sources who spoke on customary condition of anonymity.
	   While some 500 deaths, mainly hemophiliacs, are linked to
transfusions with blood contaminated by the AIDS virus, the
ministers could be held accountable for only seven, the others
proscribed with the passage of time. More than 1,000 people were
contaminated.
	   The decision to send the officials to trial was based on the
conclusion that the three carried out a ``strategy of favoritism''
that prevented Abbott laboratories from introducing its AIDS
detection test, according to the document obtained by The AP.
	   ``The delaying action of the government ... was motivated solely
by the fear -- justified -- of the invasion of the French market by
the American competitor of Diagnostics Pasteur,'' the document
said.
	   Diagnostics Pasteur, of the Pasteur Institute, was at the time
perfecting its own AIDS test, eventually made available.
	   The government ordered AIDS tests for all blood donors in August
1985. But, reads the decision, authorities were aware of potential
contamination of blood products at the beginning of 1985,
``sufficient time for a rapid reaction ....''
	   The ministers also are taken to task in the decision for failing
to import expensive heat-treated blood free of the AIDS virus.
	   The decision charged that Fabius ``imposed from the start a line
of governmental conducted dictated solely by the industrial
imperatives of Diagnostics Pasteur.''
	   Four health officials have already been convicted in the drama.
	   The Court of Justice of the Republic, made up of 12 lawmakers
and three judges, hears cases involving government officials
charged with crimes committed while in office. It will be the first
time it has judged ministers.
	   (parf-eg)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
