<SLUG> BC-Argentina-Menem-Re-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru,0322 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Argentina's President Menem won't seek third term
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS background, TIGHTENS. &QL; 
 &UR; By KEVIN GRAY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) _ Ending months of speculation,
President Carlos Menem on Tuesday renounced his intention to seek a
third straight term in next year's presidential race.
	   The question of whether Menem would seek another term has
dominated national politics for most of the year, creating friction
in his Peronist Party and stalling important legislation.
	   A third term would have required a constitutional amendment or a
special Supreme Court ruling. His term ends Dec. 10, 1999, and the
constitution currently bars him from running again.
	   ``After a prolonged analysis, I have resolved to exclude myself
from whatever course of action to compete in 1999,'' Menem said,
flanked by his ministers, governors and other members of his party
at the presidential palace.
	   ``I don't want anything or anybody to interfere with the
objective of making Argentina a country that's worth living in,''
he said.
	   Months of Menem re-election talk caused a rift among the
Peronists, particularly with supporters of his rival for the
presidential nomination, Buenos Aires Gov. Eduardo Duhalde.
	   It also stalled much-needed tax and labor code reforms.
	   A push by Menem supporters to have him run again outraged
Duhalde, who considered himself the party's ``natural'' candidate.
	   ``This ends the internal political fighting,'' said Antonio
Cafiero, a top Peronist official.
	   Opposition leaders were skeptical about the president's
announcement.
	   ``I don't believe one word he says,'' said Carlos Alvarez, a
leader of the left-leaning opposition party, Frepaso.
	   Menem was elected in 1989 for a single six-year term. The
constitution was amended to allow him to run for a second four-year
term.
</TEXT>
