<SLUG> BC-Israel-Censored Book </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Author arrested for publishing censored book on the Internet
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to restore cycle designator &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) _ The author of a banned book detailing
the Israeli navy's search for a lost submarine, was briefly
arrested by police Tuesday for breaking military censorship by
publishing sections of his book on the Internet.
	   It was the first such arrest in Israel for publishing
information on the Internet, a justice ministry official said.
	   Police searched the home of former naval officer Mike Eldar and
confiscated his computer and personal documents before taking him
in for questioning and then to a Tel Aviv Magistrates court.
	   The court ordered Eldar to remove the sections from his Internet
site, which he did in front of police. He was then released on
16,000 shekels (dlrs 4,500) bail, Israel radio reported.
	   Eldar's book ``Dakar,'' named after the Israel submarine that
disappeared off Crete in 1968 with 69 Israeli sailors, did not pass
through Israel's military censor and sales have been banned for the
past year. An appeal is currently pending in court.
	   The book describes the search for the sub as ``not serious'' and
paints an unflattering picture of the Navy.
	   Eldar, now a journalist and author, told reporters after the
court session that it was his duty to ``to expose what this country
refuses to expose out of completely irrelevant reasons.''
	   The censor in Israel rules on the publication of news and
pictures on topics defined as security-related _ including
everything from oil supplies to immigration to government loans.
	   Journalists who defy the censor can have their press credentials
revoked or face police charges.
