<SLUG> BC-UN-Macedonia, 2nd Ld,,0526 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Council approves 50 percent increase for Macedonia peacekeepers
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: SUBS lede to recast &QL; 
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Concerned that violence in Kosovo could
spill into neighboring Macedonia, the Security Council unanimously
approved a 50 percent increase Tuesday in the strength of U.N.
peacekeepers to patrol the border between the restive province and
the former Yugoslav republic.
	   The 15-member council agreed to add about 300 troops to the
750-strong U.N. peacekeeping force for Macedonia. The council also
extended the force's mandate until Feb. 28.
	   The increase brings the force _ which includes about 340
Americans _ close to its original levels in 1992, when it was first
deployed during the Bosnian war to prevent the spread of the ethnic
conflict in other parts of the former Yugoslavia.
	   Austria's U.N. ambassador, Ernst Sucharipa, noted that the force
has since been used to contain the violence that swept through
Albania last year after the collapse of pyramid investment schemes.
	   ``Today the focus has shifted again: The conflict in Kosovo
poses a new, grave threat to peace and stability in the region,''
he said, speaking on behalf of the European Union.
	   Ethnic Albanian separatists are fighting for an independent
Kosovo from Serb-led Yugoslavia. Hundreds have been killed since a
Serb crackdown in Kosovo began in February. Guns from Albania are
widely believed to have been smuggled across the border for the
Kosovo separatists to use.
	   In its resolution, the council called on member states to
respect an embargo on Yugoslavia, ``including Kosovo, of arms and
related material of all types and shall prevent arming and training
for terrorist activities there.''
	   The majority of the new troops, 230, would be deployed at nine
new observation posts along the borders with Kosovo and Albania. In
addition, a reserve group of about 60 soldiers in two platoons
would patrol the ground and air.
	   The bulk of the new troops would come from Norway, and Sweden
also pledged to continue contributing to the force. Funding will
come from the existing U.N. peacekeeping budget.
	   China's ambassador, Qin Huasun, said he wouldn't object to the
new mandate in spite of China's belief that ``U.N. peacekepping
operations should have a proper beginning as well as a proper
conclusion.'' He called for the peacekeepers to ``respect the
political independence, sovereignty and territorial integrity,'' of
Macedonia.
	   In a July 9 letter, Macedonian Foreign Minister Blagoj
Handzinski endorsed Secretary-General Kofi Annan's recommendation
for an extended mandate as well as the option of a greater troop
presence.
	   The council didn't act on Annan's other recommendations, calling
for an increase in the number of military observers and civilian
police, but said it would consider the suggestions later.
	   The U.N. operation, formally known as the United Nations
Preventive Deployment Force, includes troops from six nations. They
are Denmark, Finland, Indonesia, Norway and Sweden in addition to
the United States.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-UN-Macedonia, 2nd Ld,; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
