<HEADER>
w1265 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yemen-MinistersAttack 2ndLd-Writethru   07-21 0353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Ministers Attacked, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0352 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORRECTS slug
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to restore Eds: Note and Writethru sequence.
 &UR; Yemen tribesmen ambush official convoy &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: EDITS, TRIMS. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ Armed tribesmen opened fire Tuesday on a
convoy carrying Yemen's interior minister and other high-ranking
officials, injuring one official. Six security guards were wounded
in an ensuing gun battle.
	   One of the officials, Gov. Naji al-Dhulaimi of al-Jawf province,
was injured in the right shoulder, the Interior Ministry said. It
did not give other details.
	   The ambush occurred in the hills that straddle al-Jawf and Marib
provinces, an oil-rich region 100 miles (160 kilometers) northeast
of San`a.
	   Al-Dhulaimi and the wounded guards were flown by helicopter to a
military hospital in San`a, police said. Three of the guards were
reportedly injured seriously.
	   The ambush was carried out by tribesmen protesting a 40 percent
government hike in fuel prices, said a tribal leader, who spoke
only on condition of anonymity.
	   He said the attackers hid behind rocks in the mountainous
terrain and began shooting as soon as the convoy of eight cars
appeared.
	   Security forces cordoned off the area after the attack and
helicopter gunships hovered in search of the attackers, witnesses
said.
	   Interior Minister Hussein Mohammed Arab and Local Administration
Minister Sadek Amin Abu Ras escaped injury. The head of the
national security organization, Ghaleb al-Qams, was also in the
convoy.
	   The ministers went to the region to check on government troops
sent in to quell the unrest, which started June 19 when the
government raised the prices of gasoline, kerosene and cooking gas
to meet International Monetary Fund demands to remove subsidies.
	   In its drive for financial reform, the government has cut other
subsidies and stepped up privatization of state-controlled
companies.
	   An official death toll from the violence has not been released,
but the Yemen Times newspaper said earlier this month that 52
people had been killed and 214 injured.
</TEXT>
