<HEADLINE>
Guyana president begins Venezuela state visit
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) _ Guyanese President Janet Jagan began a
two-day state visit to neighboring Venezuela Tuesday with trade and
a contentious territorial dispute high on the agenda.
	   Jagan took a Venezuelan military aircraft to Caracas, where she
was welcomed by President Rafael Caldera and his Cabinet.
	   Venezuela and Guyana have worked hard to patch up their
century-old border dispute in recent years. Venezuela claims
two-thirds of Guyana, or the entire mineral-rich Essequibo region.
	   Jagan on Tuesday visited the tomb of Venezuelan independence
hero Simon Bolivar and was attending a special session of Congress.
	   Venezuela's foreign minister, Miguel Burelli Rivas, said the
leaders hoped to sign accords on trade, drug trafficking and the
environment.
