r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Mexico-Banks     07-21 0285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Banks,0284 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mexican treasury secretary seeks bank reform to avert crisis
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Treasury Secretary Jose Angel Gurria said
Tuesday that financial reform bills before Congress could prevent a
recurrence of Mexico's typical end-of-presidency crises.
	   Gurria told the National Agricultural Council that past crises
involved budget and current account deficits, unmanageable debt,
dependence on oil exports, inadequate internal savings and the use
of reserves to support an unsustainable exchange rate.
	   He said the government has attacked those problems through
spending cuts, diversified exports and a free-floating currency.
	   Proposed banking reforms are now stalled in Congress, largely
due to controversy over a measure to absorb dlrs 65 billion in bank
bailout funds as public debt.
	   But Gurria said it could ward off a crisis in 2000, when
President Ernesto Zedillo's six-year term ends. A series of
economic crises have coincided with the end of recent presidential
terms, making many Mexicans jittery about the end of his term.
	   ``This package (of reforms) seems to us to be the way to counter
vulnerability,'' Gurria said.
	   ``We have seen how expensive bank crises are; to allow the
system to collapse would have been five or six times more
expensive,'' Gurria added.
	   Absorbing bank debt would raise public debt to 42 percent of
gross domestic product from around 28 percent, but Gurria said it
would still be below levels of other industrialized countries.
	   The opposition-dominated Congress wants to audit the bailout
fund, charging that the bailout fund includes bad loans extended to
large debtors who could pay them back but don't.
</TEXT>
