<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Canada-Dominatrix Trial,0432 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Undercover officer testifies at dominatrix trial in Canada
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEWMARKET, Ontario (AP) _ An undercover police officer testified
Tuesday about his experiences in the home of a dominatrix charged
with running a bawdy house in a Toronto suburb.
	   ``It was getting to me,'' Constable Stephen Baird of York Region
police said of watching a woman spank a man with a bamboo stick.
``I was shocked that this person was getting hit... But there were
no cries.''
	   A police videotape was played in court as Baird described the
inside of Terri-Jean Bedford's home, equipped with eight theme
rooms, including a doctor's office, a kitchen, a schoolroom and a
downstairs dungeon.
	   During his first visit there as an undercover customer, Baird
told court he saw two woman slapping and humiliating a man
introduced as Arthur.
	   Naked from the waist down, except for a pair of women's shiny
thigh-high stiletto boots, Arthur wore a straitjacket and a leather
hood. He was chained to a pole, while the women taunted and beat
him, Baird said.
	   Baird only appeared uncomfortable when he recounted an incident
in the candlelit dungeon in which Morgan ordered him to pull down
his pants and underwear.
	   ``I pulled down my jeans ... I was wearing a Coors Lite T-shirt
that day _ and I was thankful for the length of it,'' he said.
	   Baird told staff at the bungalow on later occasions that he
preferred voyeuristic activities and simply wanted to watch.
	   Police raided Bedford's home in Thornhill just north of Toronto
four years ago. She catered to her clients' elaborate fantasies as
Madame de Sade _ and earned dlrs 100,000 (dlrs 75,000 U.S.) a year
doing so.
	   She and three others were charged but the case was dismissed
when it was ruled the charges were too vague and prosecutors
refused to specify what Bedford, 39, had done to warrant arrest.
	   The Ontario Court of Appeal overturned the dismissal and ordered
her to stand trial. The Supreme Court of Canada upheld that
decision last year.
	   A person is guilty of keeping a bawdy house if it can be proven
that prostitution or indecent acts occurred there but at the heart
of the case is the delicate question of what actually constitutes
sex.
	   Defense lawyer Alan Young maintains that although whipping,
spanking and fantasy role play may sexually arouse some folks, the
aim isn't sexual gratification.
	   Bedford, who could face a maximum of two years behind bars if
found guilty, is adamant nothing illegal occurred in her home.
	   ``No sex took place,'' she said outside court. 	   
</TEXT>
