<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Colombia-Congress Probe,0394 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Court investigates legislators who cleared President Samper of drug
</HEADLINE>
charges &QL; 
 &UR; By JARED KOTLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ Colombia's Supreme Court is opening an
investigation into 110 legislators who voted two years ago to clear
President Ernesto Samper in connection with a dlrs 6 million
campaign donation from the Cali drug cartel.
	   Legal experts are debating whether the inquiry exposes Samper,
who steps down in August, to possible new criminal charges in the
scandal that crippled and discredited his presidency.
	   ``There is no legal precedent in the history of the country,''
said a top Supreme Court official who spoke on condition he not be
identified.
	   But the Supreme Court action, which follows a two-year court
review of documents and testimony relating to the 1994 Samper
campaign, was seen as an implicit statement that Samper should not
have been absolved.
	   ``In Samper's case the evidence was overwhelming. They proved
his responsibility,'' said retired former Justice Minister Enrique
Parejo, one of a handful of citizens who filed for the Supreme
Court review.
	   A House of Representatives dominated by ruling Liberal Party
loyalists voted 111-to-43 on June 13, 1996 to drop charges of
illicit enrichment, falsifying documents, electoral fraud and
cover-up against Samper.
	   With the vote Samper survived what Colombians called the ``trial
of the century.'' But his government was weakened and discredited
internationally. Convinced of his guilt, the U.S. government
revoked Samper's visa.
	   Many accused the representatives _ one of whom is dead and only
47 of whom remain in congress_ of acting out of political loyalty
to Samper or in return for political favors, government posts and
pork-barrel projects.
	   Former representative Heyne Mogollon, who led Samper's defense
in Congress, was called to testify Tuesday, beginning a process
expected to last from 6 to 8 months and which could lead to prison
terms of 3 to 8 years for legislators who are convicted.
	   But Mogollon did not arrive in court, and his testimony was
rescheduled for Wednesday.
	   Samper, who steps down August 7, has stood by claims he was
unaware of the drug money entering his campaign and did not
improperly seek to influence the legislators who investigated him.
</TEXT>
