<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Trinidad-Hanging,0195 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Judge blocks execution of murderer
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PORT-OF-SPAIN, Trinidad and Tobago (AP) _ A judge on Tuesday
blocked the execution of a convicted murderer in Trinidad and
Tobago, saying he has already been subjected to cruel and inhuman
punishment in prison.
	   Darrin Thomas, 29, was on death row for slitting a taxi driver's
throat in 1993. High Court Justice Peter Jamadar ordered his death
sentence overturned, saying Thomas had been jailed without
sufficient light, handcuffed during exercise breaks and given
inadequate food.
	   Government lawyer Russell Martineau said he would appeal the
ruling to the Trinidad and Tobago Court of Appeals.
	   Jamadar rejected defense lawyers' arguments that the government
must wait for the Inter-American Court on Human Rights to hear an
appeal by Thomas. Trinidad and Tobago has accused the court of
dragging its feet on such appeals and has said it will drop out of
an Organization of American States accord allowing them.
	   Trinidad and Tobago has led recent resistence in the Caribbean
to pressure by Britain to eliminate the death penalty in former
British colonies.
</TEXT>
