<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-Hernandez Complaint, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0559 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Marlins pitcher drops objections to restraining order
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Rewrites throughout to INSERT quotes and additional details;
Moving on news and sports lines &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Photos MHH101, 102 and 103 &QL; 
 &UR; By STEVEN WINE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MIAMI (AP) _ Florida Marlins pitcher Livan Hernandez decided
that one day of court testimony about his personal life was enough,
and he dropped objections Tuesday to a restraining order sought by
his former girlfriend.
	   The order means Hernandez must have no contact with Alina
Elgarresta for at least a year.
	   Hernandez initially contested the order, then changed his mind
after testimony Monday in Miami-Dade Circuit Court by Elgarresta,
who said the 23-year-old pitcher physically abused her.
	   Hernandez's attorney, Manny Vazquez, noted that his client
pitched poorly in a 5-3 loss Monday night to Milwaukee after
spending the day in court. The attorney said Hernandez was eager to
put the case and his relationship with Elgarresta in the past.
	   ``What she wants is that Livan doesn't bother her anymore, and
he has no problem with that,'' Vazquez told Judge Amy Karan. ``He
wants to get on with his life.''
	   Elgarresta, 25, said she was surprised that Hernandez at first
contested the restraining order.
	   ``I feel sorry for him,'' she said. ``I hope he sees what he's
done.''
	   Hernandez would be subject to arrest for violation of the order,
which requires that he stay at least 500 feet away from Elgarresta
and have no communication with her. Such an arrest could result in
a sentence of up to a year in jail.
	   Hernandez could have agreed to the order Monday and prevented
Elgarresta's damaging testimony. Failing to do so may have been a
mistake, Hernandez's attorney admitted.
	   ``We didn't want to prolong this,'' Vazquez said. ``It was
draining to him. It has affected his professional life. It has
affected his pitching. He wanted to end it.''
	   A clause was included in the order allowing Hernandez onto the
Biltmore Golf Course, where he plays regularly. Elgarresta has a
home on the third hole, a coincidence that prompted chuckles in the
courtroom.
	   ``Obviously, Mr. Hernandez, if any balls are hit into her yard,
start with new balls,'' the judge said. ``I don't want anybody
going on her property to get balls or otherwise.''
	   Hernandez, last year's World Series most valuable player, began
dating Elgarresta in November 1997. She testified Monday that
before they broke up in June, he punched her, slapped her, kicked
her and pinned her down and plucked the hairs off her head
one-by-one.
	   Hernandez didn't speak in court, but afterwards he denied the
allegations.
	   ``Nothing happened,'' he said. ``I didn't hit her nor did I push
or scratch her. Everybody knows how I am ... and I don't do that to
a woman because I don't have the need to. ...
	   ``My worry is baseball, and it's affecting it a bit now because
I had this problem in court,'' he said. ``I feel good and content,
and I will go on with my career. About the woman, that's all
forgotten.''
	   While Elgarresta signed legal papers following the hearing,
Hernandez signed autographs for spectators in the courtroom. Many
of them cheered when he headed for an exit.
</TEXT>
