<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Senior Open,0427 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
John Bland, three others withdraw from Senior Open
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JOHN NADEL &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ John Bland, who finished second behind Graham
Marsh in the 1997 U.S. Senior Open, withdrew from this year's
competition on Tuesday because his wife is ill.
	   Bland returned to his home in South Africa.
	   The 19th U.S. Senior Open, the fourth and final major on the
Senior PGA Tour, begins Thursday at the 6,906-yard (6,284-meter),
par-71 Riviera Country Club. A purse of dlrs 1.5 million and a top
prize of dlrs 267,500 are being offered.
	   Marsh, who beat Bland by one shot with a 72-hole score of 280 at
the Olympia Fields, Illinois Country Club, last year, is back to
defend his title. The 54-year-old Australian is in search of his
first victory since that time.
	   Among others in the field of 156 are co-favorites Gil Morgan and
Hale Irwin, Jack Nicklaus, Arnold Palmer, Larry Nelson, Jay Sigel,
Peter Oosterhuis, Isao Aoki, Dave Stockton, Jim Colbert and Bob
Charles.
	   Tommy Aaron withdrew from the tournament on Monday due to a
sprained ankle, and Bud Allin and Jim Dent also pulled out Tuesday.
Allin withdrew due to illness, while Dent didn't give a reason for
dropping out.
	   Morgan and Irwin have dominated the senior tour.
	   Irwin, 53, has earned a tour-leading dlrs 1,735,250, and has won
four tournaments including one major _ the PGA Seniors
Championship. He also won the Ameritech Senior last weekend.
	   His lowest finish in 13 tournaments this year is a tie for
fifth.
	   Morgan, 51, ranks second on the earnings list at dlrs 1,325,793.
He also has four wins including two majors _ The Tradition and the
Ford Senior Players Championship. He has finished in the top 10 in
10 of his 15 tournaments this year.
	   Morgan finished second in the PGA Seniors Championship, while
Irwin was fourth in The Tradition and second in the Ford Senior
Players Championship.
	   Irwin is averaging 68.58 strokes per round this year and Morgan
69.80. No other player is averaging less than 70.
	   ``It's going to come down to who makes putts,'' Marsh said. ``I
would give myself a reasonable chance of playing well here. Whether
it's going to be good enough to win, I don't know.''
	   Marsh said there's no question in his mind that Morgan and Irwin
are the players to beat.
	   ``I think it will be under par,'' Marsh said when asked his
opinion on what it will take to win. ``The way Gil and Hale have
been playing, it might be 10-under-par.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
