<SLUG> BC-Canada-Dominatrix-Trial-Facts,0227 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With BC-Canada-Dominatrix Trial
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By the Associated Press

<TEXT>
	   Some facts about the legal battles of a dominatrix whose trial
opened Tuesday near Toronto.
	    &UR; WHO: Terri-Jean Bedford, 39, known professionally as Madame de
Sade, former proprietor of a nine-bedroom ``bondage bungalow'' in
Thornhill, Ontario, north of Toronto.
	    &UR; WHAT: Bedford specialized in fulfilling her clients' fantasies,
such as role-playing, domination, spanking and fetish work. Her
bungalow was divided into several theme rooms, including a
classroom, a nursery, a parlor, a dungeon and a theatre.
	    &UR; CLIENTS: Bedford catered to many wealthy patrons _ lawyers,
doctors, even judges _ as well as an assortment of cross-dressers
and middle-class sado-masochists.
	    &UR; LEGAL: The case against Bedford was originally dismissed when
it was ruled the 1994 charges against her for keeping a bawdy house
were too vague. The Ontario Court of Appeal overturned the
dismissal and the Supreme Court of Canada upheld that decision last
year. In April, her lawyers were removed from the case over a
conflict of interest.
	    &UR; QUOTE: ``I pulled down my jeans ... I was wearing a Coors Lite
T-shirt that day _ and I was thankful for the length of it.''
Undercover Const. Stephen Baird of York Region police testifies
about being told to disrobe.
</TEXT>
