<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Amateur Year,0748 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1998 shaping up as the year of the amateur
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DOUG FERGUSON &QC; 
 &UR; AP Golf Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SOUTHPORT, England (AP) _ The scene at the practice green looked
more like horseplay at a junior tournament, rather than preparation
for golf's oldest championship.
	   Four hours before he teed off in the final pairing of the third
round at the British Open, Justin Rose was hitting chip shots from
one side of the green to the other, landing the ball closer and
closer to where Sergio Garcia was putting.
	   As Rose walked across the green, he stopped one of Garcia's
putts from going in the hole, flipped up the ball with his wedge,
and flung it back at the Spaniard's feet.
	   Their eyes met and laughter erupted _ a couple of amateurs who
acted as if they owned the joint.
	   That seems to be the case this year at major championships.
	   First it was Matt Kuchar, who dazzled the Masters with his smile
and captivated U.S. Open with a game beyond his 20 years.
	   He missed the cut at Royal Birkdale, but roamed behind the ropes
in the third round as Rose, the 17-year-old from England, refused
to let the magnitude of the British Open spoil a good time.
	   Garcia, the 18-year-old British Amateur champion known as ``El
Nino,'' was never in contention after a first-round 69. But then,
he never came close to a round in the 80s, either _ the kind of
disaster that befell defending Open champion Justin Leonard, Phil
Mickelson and Fred Couples.
	   ``These players are young, they're strong, they start at early
ages, the intimidation factor is not there,'' said 41-year-old Mark
O'Meara, the Masters and British Open champion.
	   ``They're going out and letting it wing and having fun.''
	   Golf just seems to keep getting fresh faces to expand its
appeal.
	   That includes Jenny Chausiriporn, who came the closest to
pulling off the unthinkable of winning a major championship. She
took Se Ri Pak to a 20-hole playoff at the U.S. Women's Open three
weeks ago.
	   Until this year, golf hasn't had an amateur make this kind of an
impact since Tiger Woods. But even Woods never caused this much
stir at a major before turning pro.
	   When he was 17, like Rose, Woods missed the cut in all three of
his professional tournaments. His best finish at a major was a tie
for 22nd at the 1996 British Open, when he shot a 66 in the second
round to tie the record for lowest round by an amateur.
	   Rose became the third amateur to shoot 66 at an Open in the
second round at Birkdale. He tied for fourth, the best finish by an
amateur at the Open in 45 years, then said he was turning pro.
	   ``Being so young, I know that it would be very difficult for me
to turn pro at that age, because obviously my game really wasn't
ready for it,'' Woods said. ``The key for him right now is to be
consistent, because the media and the press are going to build him
up to be something pretty big.''
	   One British tabloid reported that Rose already has agreed to a
dlrs 526,000 deal with a club manufacturer.
	   Kuchar, should he decide to turn pro before the U.S. Amateur
next month at Oak Hill, could fetch at least four times that much
in the United States. Asked if his son could turn pro before
defending at the Amateur, Peter Kuchar nodded and said, ``Maybe.''
	   Garcia might not be far behind. Indications are he will play the
Masters next year as the British Amateur champion, then turn pro.
He'll be 19 in January, the same age Seve Ballesteros and Jose
Maria Olazabal turned pro.
	   Kuchar and Rose share that same wonderful smile _ a reminder to
casual fans and pros alike that golf is a game to be enjoyed.
	   Once they give up their amateur status, though, that sweet
innocence of youth will carry them only so far. Both have clearly
shown this year that they have a game to go head-to-head with
golf's best.
	   It could also be that they have played their best on golf's
biggest stages.
	   Kuchar wasn't even the best player at Georgia Tech. His
teammate, freshman Bryce Molder, was named the college player of
the year. And Rose only last month failed to advance out of the
first round of the British Amateur.
	   But those are questions for later. It's not often an amateur
like Rose can grab so much attention in a major, let alone four of
them in one year.
	   ``The kid is obviously playing great,'' said Nick Faldo. ``He
should just go out there and enjoy it.''
</TEXT>
