<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs, 1st Ld-Writethru,0489 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Guatemala, Peru, Mexico and Nicaragua.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with new items. Contains items from
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) _ A hand grenade uncovered near a soccer
field accidentally detonated, killing a mother and six children,
newspapers reported Tuesday.
	   The children dug up the grenade and brought it to one of their
mothers, who was trying to clean it when the explosive detonated,
the reports said.
	   A 30-year-old woman, her 10- and 12-year-old sons and their four
friends, ages 9 to 12, were all killed.
	   The accident occurred Sunday in the village of Caoba, about 140
miles (225 kilometers) north of Guatemala City.
	   The grenade was apparently left over from Guatemala's 36-year
civil war, which ended in 1996.
	   ___
	   LIMA, Peru (AP) _ President Alberto Fujimori's popularity has
fallen nine percentage points in the past month due to discontent
with high poverty and a lack of jobs, a poll released Tuesday
showed.
	   Fujimori was popular with 31 percent of those polled while 55
percent said they disapproved of his performance as president, a
poll of Lima residents by the private company Apoyo showed.
Fourteen percent had no opinion.
	   Fujimori was re-elected in a landslide in 1995, partly due to
his effectiveness in fighting leftist guerrillas and capturing
their top leaders.
	   But lingering poverty and the failure of his economic policies
to create well-paid jobs have eroded his support over the years,
Loli said.
	   Apoyo surveyed 510 people in the capital Lima on July 17, 18
with a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percent.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ About two dozen federal anti-drug police
raided a municipal police station in the Pacific Coast resort of
Mazatlan to rescue three arrested colleagues, newspapers reported
Tuesday.
	   Mazatlan city police said three federal agents were arrested
Sunday night for shooting into the air while driving drunkenly
along a city street.
	   The government's Notimex news agency reported that later that
night, about 25 federal anti-drug agents, some armed with automatic
rifles, surrounded the city police station and forced the release
of the arrested men.
	   ___
	   MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) _ Officials said Tuesday that 14 inmates
fled a police station in western Managua as authorities were busy
guarding celebrations of a political anniversary.
	   The escape occurred Sunday night while police were concentrated
at the Plaza of the Republic to keep order during a celebration of
the 19th anniversary of the Sandinista guerrilla triumph over the
Somoza family dictatorship.
	   A policeman who arrived Monday morning discovered the escape.
The inmates apparently had cut through the iron bars of their
cells.
	   Several of the escapees were serving short sentences while
others were facing trial on charges of murder, armed robbery or
rape.
</TEXT>
