<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Notes,0895 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Strong finish puts Watts' career at a crossroads
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DOUG FERGUSON &QC; 
 &UR; AP Golf Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SOUTHPORT, England (AP) _ The next step for Brian Watts could be
as difficult as that bunker shot he hit on the 72nd hole to force a
playoff with British Open champion Mark O'Meara.
	   Watts, who has played the Japanese tour the past six years, won
dlrs 329,000 for his runner-up finish at Royal Birkdale.
	   That was enough to place him 61st on the PGA Tour money list.
And with only 14 events left this year, that should be more than
enough to keep him in the top 125 at the end of the season, which
would make him eligible for the tour next year.
	   ``In an ideal situation, I think I would enjoy playing on the
U.S. tour,'' said Watts, who lives in Edmond, Oklahoma and makes
about six trips across the Pacific each year. ``I've got almost a
1-year-old boy now, and it would be nice to be closer to him. So I
would like to play here.''
	   But the Japanese tour has been awfully good to Watts, and he
doesn't want to turn his back on it that quickly.
	   Not only does he have Japanese sponsors, but he might have given
up on his career if not for that tour.
	   He played only one year on the PGA Tour, in 1991, and missed the
cut in half of the tournaments. The former NCAA champion from
Oklahoma State failed qualifying school in 1988, 1989, 1991 and
1992 before going to Asia in desperation _ and finding a pot of
gold waiting for him.
	   ``I'm very lucky to be playing in Japan right now,'' he said.
	   He has won 11 tournaments in Asia and averages about dlrs
800,000 a year in earnings.
	   Along with his British Open winnings, Watts will have even more
chances to move up the PGA Tour money list without playing in
America. His world ranking improved to No. 23, and he should be
eligible for the dlrs 5 million purses in the three World
Championship of Golf events next year.
	   But playing the PGA Tour could also cut into his bank account.
Watts concedes it is deeper, ``strong from No. 1 to 156 players
each week.'' He would probably have to finish around 35th on the
money list, not particularly easy, to earn what he makes in Japan.
	   Watts was in no mood to decide his future after losing by two
strokes to Mark O'Meara in Sunday's playoff.
	   ``I guess I'll make up my mind some other time,'' he said.
	   Whenever that is, the decision won't be as easy as it seems.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; DALY DOINGS: &LR;  Along with his battle against alcoholism, John
Daly was showing plenty of fight on the golf course earlier this
year.
	   Not only was he playing the most consistent golf of his career,
his only final round over par was at Bay Hill _ he shot 85 thanks
to an 18 on the sixth hole, where he hit six 3-wood shots into the
water trying to cut the corner.
	   But ever since The Players Championship, where he celebrated one
year of sobriety with a closing 69 that tied him for 16th, Daly has
looked more like the player who often gave up when things didn't go
his way.
	   He has missed the cut in five of 10 tournaments since then, and
his best finish was a tie for 33rd at the Masters. In the five
tournaments in which he played on the weekend, his final-round
average is 77.4.
	   Daly laughed off his 18 at Bay Hill, but was in no mood to
discuss the 10 he took on the 18th hole of the second round at the
British Open _ five shots out of a greenside bunker, giving him an
80 and an early trip home.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; SAME LANGUAGE, DIFFERENT TRANSLATION: &LR;  In transcripts of
interviews and in some of England's newspapers, American players
sounded a wee bit British this week.
	   On a day when security was tight for players and fans alike, Ben
Crenshaw was quoted in one tabloid as saying that police had ``even
searched the boot.''
	   That's the trunk of a car, not a shoe.
	   And try to imagine these words from Jim Furyk, who couldn't get
a putt to fall in his final round of 70 that left him tied for
fourth: ``I'm rottenly mad.''
	   Indeed.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; WESTWOOD HO: &LR;  The manager for English star Lee Westwood
realizes there are fences to be mended, especially since the
25-year-old pulled out of the MCI Classic and the Western Open.
	   Both tournaments were the week after a major, and Westwood cited
fatigue.
	   But Andrew ``Chubby'' Chandler was offended by the remarks of
Greg McLaughlin, the Western Open tournament director who said that
Westwood would never be invited back.
	   ``When a guy comes out and says you're not welcome, he is just
not going to play,'' Chandler said. ``Lee doesn't fall out with
anybody. A nicer kid you won't find.''
	   Chandler said Westwood was emotionally drained after his tie for
seventh at the U.S. Open, and that he could not have properly
prepared for the British Open if he had stayed for the Western.
	   After returning from San Francisco, Westwood was 15th at the
Irish Open and then won his third European tour event in four
starts a week later at Loch Lomond. He tied for 64th at Royal
Birkdale.
	   Chandler said Westwood probably will play the MCI Classic next
year. And he could still show up at the Western.
	   By winning in New Orleans, Westwood earned a two-year exemption
on the PGA Tour if he wants to join _ and then he could play any
tournament he wants.
</TEXT>
