<SLUG> BC-Puerto Rico-Telephone Sale,0212 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Puerto Rico sticks with GTE in telephone company sale
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Puerto Rico is sticking with GTE
Corp. as the lead buyer of its state-owned telephone company,
rejecting a rival bid by Spain's Telefonica Internacional S.A.,
Gov. Pedro Rossello said Tuesday.
	   A consortium led by Stamford, Connecticut-based GTE offered
about dlrs 2 billion for a controlling interest in Puerto Rico
Telephone Co. Rossello had signed a deal with the consortium in
May.
	   Pending its approval by U.S. federal agencies, the contract
allowed Puerto Rico to consider competing bids, and Telefonica
reportedly offered a similar amount earlier this month. GTE came
back with an ``enhanced'' counter-offer.
	   Rossello cited technology transfer and the ability to quickly
complete the deal in explaining his decision to stay with GTE.
	   ``This decision is final and firm,'' the governor said in a
broadcast message.
	   Some 6,400 union telephone workers went on strike June 18 to
protest the privatization and demand job guarantees. Talks to end
the strike have broken down.
	   More than 293,000 customers lacked intra-island long distance
service Tuesday because of strike-related sabotage, the telephone
company said.
</TEXT>
