<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-People-Spacey </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kevin Spacey forsakes one marathon for another
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Talk about devotion!
	   Kevin Spacey is taking a night off from his marathon London
stage role in Eugene O'Neill's ``The Iceman Cometh'' in order to
undertake a separate kind of marathon - making it to Los Angeles
for the premiere Wednesday of his film ``The Negotiator'' and then
back to London in time for his play on Thursday.
	   As Spacey described it July 21, on Tuesday evening he performs
as usual his highly acclaimed performance at the Old Vic playing
anguished salesman, Hickey.
	   The next morning, he takes the Concorde to New York and changes
to a plane for Los Angeles. After the premiere, he boards the
so-called ``red eye'' back to New York in time for the morning
Concorde back to London on Thursday. That flight in turn gets him
to Heathrow Airport a scant 90 minutes before Thursday's
performance of the play starts.
	   ``Hopefully, nothing will be delayed,'' said Spacey, adding that
he and his colleagues ``have a good ending of the first act if I'm
not there.''
	   Spacey has agreed to an extra performance of the play on Sunday
- the Oscar-winning actor's 39th birthday - to make up for the
missed show. The sellout run of ``Iceman'' ends August 1.
	   ``The Negotiator'' opens across the United States on July 29.
	   (mw-rs) 	   
</TEXT>
