<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Azerbaijan-Oil </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
British companies sign oil and construction deals in Azerbaijan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ British Petroleum PLC said Tuesday it plans to
invest at least dlrs 75 million in a new venture to explore for oil
offshore in Azerbaijan's Caspian Sea.
	   The agreement between BP and the State Oil Co. of the Azerbaijan
Republic was the biggest of four deals signed Tuesday by British
companies during a visit by Azerbaijan's president, Geidar Aliev.
	   Although the British government said the deals could be worth
billions, BP stayed cautious about how much it will invest, saying
it first needed to test the fields where it plans to explore for
oil. BP and Norway's Statoil will each have 15 percent of the
Caspian Sea deal, while the Azerbaijani company, known as SOCAR,
will hold 40 percent and allocate the rest of the equity later.
	   The deal is the third major BP project in Azerbaijan, after a
recent successful find that is producing 70,000 barrels of crude a
day and the start of drilling on another contract.
	   Also Tuesday, Ramco Energy PLC said it had signed an onshore
production sharing agreement for the rehabilitation, exploration
and development of three onshore oil fields in Azerbaijan, with an
option for further exploration.
	   A feasibility study concluded that the fields hold at least 5
billion barrels of oil, Ramco said in announcing the 50-50 deal
with SOCAR.
	   Terms were not disclosed.
	   The Foreign Office cited a third oil contract that was signed
Tuesday between Monument Oil and Gas and Azerbaijan for the British
firm to take a 12.5 percent stake in a project to develop the
offshore Inam block, 18 miles (30 kms) off the southeastern coast
of Azerbaijan.
	   The Azerbaijanis will hold 50 percent of the deal, while the
American oil giant Amoco Corp. will take a 25 percent stake and
Central Fuel Caspian Sea Ltd. will take the remaining 12.5 percent.
	   Morrison Construction Group also finalized an agreement for the
development of a Hilton Hotel and an office complex in the
Azerbaijani capital, Baku.
	   (rs-db) 	   
</TEXT>
