<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Boxing-Tyson-License,0385 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Adviser says he didn't think Nevada would license boxer
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LAS VEGAS (AP) _ The adviser for Mike Tyson went to New Jersey
to seek a license for the boxer because he did not think he would
be re-licensed in Nevada, according to a published report.
	   ``If I believed Mike Tyson would be licensed in Nevada, I
wouldn't have gone to New Jersey first,'' Shelly Finkel told the
Las Vegas Sun from his New York office on Monday.
	   Finkel said he didn't believe his client would be re-licensed in
Nevada if and when he applied. Tyson's license was revoked by the
Nevada State Athletic Commission for at least one year for biting
Evander Holyfield's ears in a fight here last July. The one-year
period expired July 9.
	   Instead of applying in Nevada as expected, Finkel had Tyson
apply in New Jersey last Friday. A hearing on that application is
scheduled July 29.
	   Finkel's implications upset Dr. Elias Ghanem, NSAC chairman.
	   ``How does he know how we'd vote?'' Ghanem asked. ``What he said
doesn't make sense unless he has some other agenda.
	   ``This angers me,'' Ghanem told the Sun. ``I've had no contact
whatsoever with Shelly Finkel and I know for a fact no one could
have told him Mike Tyson has no chance to be re-licensed in
Nevada.''
	   Ghanem, vice chairman Dr. James Nave and NSAC executive director
Marc Ratner each said they have intentionally avoided discussing
the subject of Tyson's reinstatement.
	   ``I can't tell you how anyone would vote because we've made it a
point not to discuss it with anyone, including among ourselves,''
Ratner said. ``But if three of the five would have voted for
reinstating Tyson, he'd be reinstated. It's as simple as that.''
	   Finkel said if the Nevada commission would commit to
re-licensing Tyson, he would come to Nevada instead.
	   Tyson hasn't fought in New Jersey since defeating Alex Stewart
in 1990.
	   Ghanem said he feels Nevada should be the state to decide
Tyson's future.
	   ``I expect the state of New Jersey to honor our suspension,''
Ghanem said. ``If Mike Tyson is to be licensed, the place for him
to apply is in Nevada.
	   ``We have a mutual respect between states,'' the chairman said.
``We in Nevada expect them to honor our suspensions.''
</TEXT>
