<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rival parties split seven parliamentary by-elections
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ The main opposition party won four of
seven parliamentary by-elections, retaining its slim majority in
the one-house National Assembly, final returns showed Wednesday.
	   The by-elections Tuesday increased the number of seats the main
opposition Grand National Party holds in the 299-member National
Assembly to 151, a two-seat majority.
	   President Kim Dae-jung's party, the National Congress for New
Politics, won two seats, boosting its parliamentary membership to
88.
	   The ruling coalition party, the United Liberal Democrats, picked
up one seat, raising the number of its national legislators to 48.
There are also 11 independent and minor opposition party members.
	   The rival parties equally split four seats at stake in Seoul and
Kyonggi province, which surrounds the capital. The main opposition
party won two seats in its provincial strongholds, while the ruling
coalition party picked up one seat in Pusan, the nation's second
largest city.
	   The by-elections were held to fill seats vacated by deaths as
well as court rulings that nullified previous elections over
various election law violations.
	   Before Tuesday's balloting, all of the seven seats were held by
opposition members.
	   For the ruling camp, the outcome of Tuesday's by-elections was
disappointing. It had hoped to sweep most of the seats at stake and
deprive the main opposition party of its parliamentary majority.
	   The ruling party has persistently complained that the opposition
has been a stumbling block to the government's reform policies.
	   The main opposition party largely represents South Korea's
conservative groups, which ruled the country for nearly a half
century until it was defeated in last December's presidential
elections.
	   A record-low voter turnout of 40.1 percent marked Tuesday's
by-elections, held in the midst of a deepening economic crisis.
South Korea's battered economy was bailed out by the International
Monetary Fund in December. 	   
</TEXT>
