<SLUG> BC-Canadian Briefs,0769 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New money for pursuit of war criminals welcomed
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Dollar amounts are in Canadian dollars
 &UR; By The Associated Press

<TEXT>
	   OTTAWA (AP) _ The federal government is pumping $46.8 million
over three years into the pursuit of war criminals past and
present, a welcome move by groups critical of the government's
lacklustre performance in the past.
	   ``I think it's a very strong message that the Canadian
government is sending out that Canada is no longer open to war
criminals,'' said Irving Abella, a York University history
professor and chairman of the war crimes committee of the Canadian
Jewish Congress.
	   The money will allow the Justice Department to open 14 new
investigations of Second World War cases. It also lets the
Immigration Department step up its efforts against alleged war
criminals from contemporary conflicts.
	   The government said the money will also enhance co-ordination
among war-crimes investigators and those who prosecute or deport
war criminals, or those involved in investigating crimes against
humanity.
	   ---
 &UR; Float plane crash lands with campers aboard
	   FITZROY HARBOR, Ontario (AP) _ An aerial field trip above the
lush Ottawa River valley turned terrifying for a group of
disadvantaged children Tuesday when the float plane carrying them
back to summer camp flipped over as it tried to land on water.
	   None of the eight passengers, including six children and their
camp counsellor, were injured. One girl suffered a minor cut and
two children were taken to hospital in nearby Shawville, Quebec,
for observation, said Const. David Young of the Ontario Provincial
Police.
	   Witnesses said the plane landed and then immediately went belly
up. Within minutes, one of the plane doors opened and the
passengers came out wearing life jackets.
	   ---
 &UR; Police shoot man during domestic dispute
	   CALGARY (AP) _ Calgary police shot and killed a man after
watching him stab a woman who was trying to remove a child from his
arms.
	   Police were called to a house after someone called 911 and
immediately hung up. When they arrived, they found a young man on
the back deck of the house holding a child in his arms while
wielding a knife.
	   An older woman, believed to be the grandmother, came on to the
deck and tried to take the child away from the Manitoba As officers
watched from below, the man stabbed the woManitoba
	   Three officers opened fire with their service revolvers. The man
died at the scene.
	   The woman is in stable condition.
	   The child, who had escaped from the man's grasp during the
stabbing and had run back inside the house, did not witness the
shooting.
	   ---
 &UR; Drunk driver who killed son ordered jailed
	   BROCKVILLE, Ontario (AP) _ An impaired driver who killed his
four-year-old son and injured his two-year-old son in a single-car
accident will do time in a jail instead of at home, an appeal court
has ruled.
	   The Ontario Court of Appeal has overturned a conditional
sentence granted Stephen Blakeley by Provincial Court Judge Kenneth
Pedlar.
	   That sentence allowed Blakeley to serve his time at home except
for going to work and visiting his surviving son.
	   Blakeley, 39, a molecular biologist at Queen's University in
Kingston, pleaded guilty to impaired driving causing death and
impaired driving causing bodily harm for the Sept. 27 accident.
	   Pedlar agreed to allow Blakeley to serve his sentence of two
years less a day in the community rather than in a provincial
institution. He found Blakeley was not a danger to the public and
was working to correct his drinking problem.
	   However, the appeal court said the sentence was too lenient and
that Pedlar didn't put enough weight on the need to deter others
from committing similar crimes.
	   ---
 &UR; Bone-marrow plea prompts significant response
	   HALIFAX (AP) _ The Red Cross in Nova Scotia has been swamped
with offers of help for a young Ottawa girl who might die without a
bone-marrow transplant.
	   Fourteen-month-old Haley MacDonald suffers from a rare and fatal
disorder called Hurler's disease. She's missing an enzyme in her
blood that breaks down mucus.
	   The girl's father, Mike MacDonald, was born in Antigonish, Nova
Scotia A Halifax newspaper story last weekend has prompted more
than 100 calls to the Red Cross.
	   Her father is asking people to register for bone-marrow
donations.
	   Unless a successful match is found within the next two months,
doctors fear the child might not live to see her 10th birthday.
</TEXT>
