<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Briefs,1333 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A Package of Caribbean News Briefs
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; TRINIDAD AND TOBAGO: Judge blocks execution of murderer &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PORT-OF-SPAIN, Trinidad and Tobago (AP) _ A judge on Tuesday
blocked the execution of a convicted murderer in Trinidad and
Tobago, saying he has already been subjected to cruel and inhuman
punishment in prison.
	   Darrin Thomas, 29, was on death row for slitting a taxi driver's
throat in 1993. High Court Justice Peter Jamadar ordered his death
sentence overturned, saying Thomas had been jailed without
sufficient light, handcuffed during exercise breaks and given
inadequate food.
	   Government lawyer Russell Martineau said he would appeal the
ruling to the Trinidad and Tobago Court of Appeals.
	   Jamadar rejected defense lawyers' arguments that the government
must wait for the Inter-American Court on Human Rights to hear an
appeal by Thomas. Trinidad and Tobago has accused the court of
dragging its feet on such appeals and has said it will drop out of
an Organization of American States accord allowing them.
 &UR; UNITED STATES: Passengers reported smoke long before ship
announcement
	   MIAMI (AP) _ Passengers aboard the giant cruise ship Ecstasy
pulled stewards into their cabins to show them smoke coming through
the vents and plumes rising from the ship's stern long before the
first announcement telling people to move to upper decks.
	   One passenger said Tuesday that an hour and 20 minutes passed
between when she first noticed the smoke and heard the first fire
alarm.
	   A welder's spark in a laundry room may have ignited lint in the
air-conditioning vents and touched off an ``explosive-type'' fire
that quickly spread two decks above to the outside mooring area,
where nylon rope fed the flames, Carnival Cruise Lines president
Bob Dickinson said.
	   Fifty-four of the nearly 3,500 people aboard suffered mostly
minor injuries.
	   Plumes of smoke shot out the back of the 855-foot-long ship
shortly after it left the Port of Miami Monday for a four-night
trip to Key West and Cozumel, Mexico.
 &UR; PUERTO RICO: Government sticks with GTE in telephone company sale
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Puerto Rico is sticking with GTE
Corp. as the lead buyer of its state-owned telephone company,
rejecting a rival bid by Spain's Telefonica Internacional S.A.,
Gov. Pedro Rossello said Tuesday.
	   A consortium led by Stamford, Connecticut-based GTE offered
about dlrs 2 billion for a controlling interest in Puerto Rico
Telephone Co. Rossello had signed a deal with the consortium in
May.
	   Pending its approval by U.S. federal agencies, the contract
allowed Puerto Rico to consider competing bids, and Telefonica
reportedly offered a similar amount earlier this month. GTE came
back with an ``enhanced'' counter-offer.
	   Rossello cited technology transfer and the ability to quickly
complete the deal in explaining his decision to stay with GTE.
	   ``This decision is final and firm,'' the governor said in a
broadcast message.
	   Some 6,400 union telephone workers went on strike June 18 to
protest the privatization and demand job guarantees.
 &UR; GUYANA: Guyanese turn to Northern Ireland for ideas on division
	   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) _ Weary of racially charged riots,
firebombings and angry rhetoric, politicians in Guyana are looking
for answers in Northern Ireland.
	   A delegation of legislators, lawyers and Information Minister
Moses Nagamootoo left for Belfast on Monday on a 10-day trip to see
how British-controlled Northern Ireland is trying to heal decades
of Protestant-Catholic division.
	   In Guyana, a former British colony on the northeast shoulder of
South America, friction between people of African and East Indian
descent erupted into violence after Afro-Guyanese accused President
Janet Jagan's party of rigging the Dec. 15 election.
	   Leaders from other Caribbean countries brokered a shaky peace
last month. Politicians agreed to rewrite Guyana's constitution to
better balance power between the ethnic groups.
	   The Guyanese delegation will meet with Irish President Mary
McAleese, former Irish Prime Minister John Bruton and other
officials, said the Washington-based National Democratic Institute,
which is sponsoring the trip.
 &UR; VENEZUELA: Guyanese president begins Venezuela state visit
	   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) _ Guyanese President Janet Jagan began a
two-day state visit to neighboring Venezuela Tuesday with trade and
a contentious territorial dispute high on the agenda.
	   Jagan took a Venezuelan military aircraft to Caracas, where she
was welcomed by President Rafael Caldera and his Cabinet.
	   Venezuela and Guyana have worked hard to patch up their
century-old border dispute in recent years. Venezuela claims
two-thirds of Guyana, or the entire mineral-rich Essequibo region.
	   Jagan on Tuesday visited the tomb of Venezuelan independence
hero Simon Bolivar and was attending a special session of Congress.
	   Venezuela's foreign minister, Miguel Burelli Rivas, said the
leaders hoped to sign accords on trade, drug trafficking and the
environment.
 &UR; JAMAICA: ``Creative thinking'' needed in parliaments, PM says
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ Lawmakers need ``new creative
thinking'' to handle increasing international cooperation and
global business, Jamaican Prime Minister P.J. Patterson told a
conference of parliamentarians Tuesday.
	   Speaking at the 23rd regional conference of the Commonwealth
Parliamentary Association in Kingston, Patterson said
multi-national businesses were pushing governments to lower
tariffs, change quotas and alter exchange controls to eliminate
boundaries between countries.
	   Lawmakers will be challenged to find solutions that can retain
sovereign powers, he said.
	   ``It cannot be business as usual. It cannot be legislation as
usual,'' he said. ``There is now a compelling need for new creative
thinking. The new world order will render us obsolete unless we
prove ourselves adequate to the task.''
 &UR; GUYANA: Lost ranger returns home
	   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) _ A forest ranger lost in the Guyanese
jungle for 10 days returned home this week, bruised and
mosquito-bitten but otherwise in good health.
	   Raymond Houston, 51, disappeared July 4 while helping teen
volunteers work on a Guyana Forestry Commission station about 90
miles (140 kilometers) southwest of Georgetown.
	   Houston, a 20-year veteran of the forestry commission, had gone
into the bush to find some students he thought were lost. He lost
his bearings in heavy rain.
	   Fighting off fatigue and mosquitoes, he hiked for days through
swamps filled with caimans and poisonous snakes. ``Once, I was so
tired I slept in a swamp holding on to a tree,'' Houston said. ``I
prayed a lot and asked God for sustenance.''
	   He stumbled out of the jungle Wednesday at a logging camp 20
miles away. He was treated for dehydration and insect bites before
being brought home on Sunday.
 &UR; BRITISH VIRGIN ISLANDS: Government eases restrictions on U.S.
horses
	   CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) _ The British Virgin
Islands will ease restrictions for race horses from the neighboring
U.S. Virgin Islands under an agreement signed Monday.
	   Previously, U.S. horses had to be put in quarantine for two
weeks before being allowed to compete at the Little A Racetrack on
the island of Tortola. The agreement eliminates the quarantine,
although horses will still have to be stabled separately.
	   British officials said they are considering a similar agreement
with Puerto Rico, another U.S. territory.
	   The changes come as the British Virgin Islands prepares for its
annual August Monday Festival race on Aug. 3.
	   The Little A Racetrack has just undergone a three year, dlrs 2
million renovation.
</TEXT>
