<SLUG> BC-AP News Digest,1062 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   WORLD AT 0000 GMT:
	   NEW:
	   _ALGERIA-UN MISSION. U.N. begins unprecedented look at Algeria
violence.
	   _TAJIKISTAN-UN. Four U.N. observers killed in ambush.
	   _ARGENTINA-MENEM-RE-ELECTION. Menem drops plans to seek third
term.
 &UR; MAIN SPOT NEWS:
	   VANIMO, Papua New Guinea _ Officials say Wednesday they are
having trouble keeping count of the dead from the tsunami that
wiped out coastal villages because rotting bodies are falling
apart. PAPUA NEW GUINEA-TSUNAMI. Recap expected by 0100 GMT. By
Rohan Sullivan. AP Photos VAN102-106.
	   PARIS _ A U.N. delegation leaves Wednesday on an unprecedented
mission to Algeria, seeking information on the sources of more than
six years of bloodshed. ALGERIA-UN MISSION. Expected by 0200 GMT.
By Elaine Ganley.
	   PRETORIA, South Africa _ After years of conjecture about
apartheid's chain of command, a former Cabinet minister details how
former President P.W. Botha allegedly ordered the destruction of a
church headquarters. SOUTH AFRICA-BOTHA. Lead has moved. By Pat
Reber. AP Photos JOH101-102.
	   TOKYO _ Just two days before a key ruling party ballot,
anticipation grows over which of three candidates seeking Japan's
prime ministership will get the nod to lead the country out of its
nagging recession. JAPAN-POLITICS. Expected by 0600 GMT.
	   WASHINGTON _ Ten years after the bombing of a Pan Am jetliner,
the United States and Britain are considering a trial of two Libyan
suspects in the Netherlands under Scottish law. BRITAIN-LOCKERBIE.
Lead has moved. By Barry Schweid.
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ An American diplomat meets with the
Yugoslav and ethnic Albanian leaders, but fighting continues in
Kosovo. YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO. Recap expected by 0300 GMT. AP Photos
PRI101-102.
	   ALSO MOVED:
	   _UN-MACEDONIA. Council increases peacekeeping mission to prevent
Kosovo violence from spreading.
	   _MACEDONIA-EXPLOSIONS. Three explosions shake Macedonia
	   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast _ There wasn't much more that Gen.
Abdulsalam Abubakar could have promised in his pledge to transform
Nigeria to civilian rule. But skeptical Nigerians have heard
countless promises of democracy before. ANALYSIS-NIGERIA'S
CYNICISM. Expected by 0300 GMT. By Tim Sullivan.
	   ALSO MOVED: NIGERIA. Critics want action to follow Nigerian
president's democracy pledge.
	   MOSCOW _ The government says it will ignore resistance from
parliament and push ahead with an austerity program planned as part
of an international bailout plan. RUSSIA-ECONOMY. Lead has moved.
By Anna Dolgov. AP Photos MOSB101-102.
	   WASHINGTON _ Asia's turmoil has sharply slowed both U.S.
economic growth and inflation, but the Federal Reserve remains
ready to raise interest rates if prices begin to rise faster,
Chairman Alan Greenspan tells Congress. US-ECONOMY. Has moved. By
Dave Skidmore. AP Photos WX107,110.
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Talks aimed at resolving a standoff
between Protestant marchers and security forces blocking them from
parading through a hostile Catholic neighborhood end without
agreement. NORTHERN IRELAND. Recap expected by 0200 GMT. AP Photo
XBFT101.
	   TEL AVIV, Israel _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu says he
wants Israeli-Palestinian negotiations over an American peace
proposal to include other issues besides a long overdue Israeli
troop withdrawal. ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS. Lead has moved. By Dafna
Linzer.
	   UNITED NATIONS _ Four members of a U.N. observer mission to
Tajikistan are killed in an ambush while patrolling the
north-central part of the country, U.N. officials say.
TAJIKISTAN-UN. Lead has moved. By Nicole Winfield.
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ Ending months of speculation,
President Carlos Menem says he will not seek a third straight term
in next year's presidential race. ARGENTINA-MENEM-RE-ELECTION. Lead
has moved. By Kevin Gray. AP Photos BAI103,104.
	   UNITED NATIONS _ The Security Council condemns the forced
withdrawal of international aid organizations from the Afghan
capital and says it supports U.N. efforts to maintain relief
operations in their absence. UN-AFGHANISTAN. Lead has moved. By
Nicole Winfield.
	   WASHINGTON _ The United States gives approval to the
International Monetary Fund to resume negotiations with Pakistan to
help avert financial disaster, despite U.S. sanctions on the
country to protest its nuclear testing. US-PAKISTAN-IMF. Has moved.
By Harry Dunphy.
	   ALSO MOVED: PAKISTAN-US-NUCLEAR. Crucial talks on bridging
differences continue Wednesday. Developments will be expedited.
	   LOOKING AHEAD: Actor Gerard Depardieu due in court in France on
a drunken driving charge Thursday.
 &UR; FEATURES:
	   PARIS _ The Zagat guide, a book of restaurant ratings used in
London and the United States, has arrived in Paris. And some French
chefs are not happy about it. FEA-FRANCE-THE PEOPLE'S GUIDEBOOK.
Expected by 0200 GMT. By Jocelyn Noveck. AP Photo PAR125.
	   SAN`A, Yemen _ Yemen is violent and lawless in many regions. Yet
tourism is booming in this Arabian Peninsula country.
FEA-YEMEN-INTREPID TRAVELERS. Expected by 0200 GMT. By Anthony
Shadid. AP Photo SAN101.
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary _ After serving nine years in prison for
espionage, Gabor Rimner just wants a clean slate in his native
country. Fed up with being a second-class citizen, the Hungarian is
seeking legal rehabilitation for himself and a dozen others accused
as Western spies. FEA-HUNGARY-SPY'S QUEST. Expected by 0200 GMT. By
Eva Kekes. AP Photo NY302.
	   VILNIUS, Lithuania _ Ten years ago, Vytautas Landsbergis
galvanized his countrymen's desires for freedom from Soviet
domination and led them on the road to independence. Today, most
see him as a relic. FEA-LITHUANIA-LANDSBERGIS FADES. Expected by
0200 GMT. By Liudas Dapkus. AP Photos NY305-306.
	   Also moved:
	   FEA-TAIWAN-BIG HERO VS VIAGRA. Traditional Asian impotency cures
face competition from Viagra. AP Photos NY107,108.
	   YOUR QUERIES: The Associated Press World Service editors in
charge are Joe Federman and Charles Gans. Questions and story
requests to The Associated Press World Service are welcome. Contact
your local AP bureau or the AP International Desk in New York,
telephone (1) 212-621-1650, fax (1) 212-621-5449. 	   
