<SLUG> BC-People and Places,,0829 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People and places in the news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Items include Jodie Foster, Madonna, Tom Hanks, King Hussein,
R Kelly. Some items have also moved as separates. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ Actress Jodie Foster is a mother for the
first time.
	   The Oscar-winning actress gave birth to a boy at 5:53 a.m.
Monday at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center, publicist Pat Kingsley said.
Charles Foster weighed 7 1/2 pounds (3.2 kilos) and was 20 1/2
inches (51 centimeters) long.
	   ``She couldn't be happier. She's happy as a lark,'' Ms. Kingsley
said.
	   Foster, whose movie credits include ``Taxi Driver'' and
``Silence of the Lambs,'' isn't married and she hasn't revealed the
name of the father.
	   The 35-year-old actress returned to her Los Angeles home with
her son on Tuesday.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ She's not the first person to waste violin
lessons.
	   Madonna has decided not to play the lead in ``50 Violins,'' a
movie about an inner-city music teacher, Miramax said Tuesday.
	   Wes Craven, the film's director, said the problem was ``genuine
mutual creative differences.''
	   Madonna's spokeswoman, Liz Rosenberg, did not immediately return
a call Tuesday.
	   Madonna spent three months learning the violin so she could play
the role of Roberta Tzavaris, who taught kids in East Harlem, Daily
Variety said.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ Ground control to davidbowie.com.
	   David Bowie said Monday he is launching his own Internet service
provider _ BowieNet _ in September at dlrs 19.95 a month.
	   BowieNet, at www.davidbowie.com, will offer high-speed Internet
service across North America and expand worldwide later in the
year. It will also offer e-mail service and special music and
entertainment access.
	   ``I wanted to create an environment where not just my fans but
all music lovers could be a part of the same community _ a single
place where the vast archives of music information could be
accessed, views stated and ideas exchanged,'' Bowie said.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   CHICAGO (AP) _ The city dropped charges that Grammy-winning
singer R. Kelly played his car stereo too loudly back in April.
	   Kelly, known for the rhythm and blues hit ``I Believe I Can
Fly,'' was arrested after he allegedly refused to a request from
police to turn it down.
	   Jennifer Hoyle, a spokeswoman for the city's law department,
would not say why prosecutors dropped the noise charges Monday.
	   Charges of disorderly conduct and failure to produce a valid
driver's license were dropped in May.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Logic stands between Tom Hanks and bad-guy
roles.
	   ``The problem is that I'm always in search of logic in
storytelling,'' he said in this week's USA Weekend. ``And the bad
guys always suffer from faulty logic.''
	   Hanks stars with Matt Damon in ``Saving Private Ryan,'' a World
War II film that left Hanks thankful he never had to go to war.
	   ``I'm glad I didn't have to fight in any war. I'm glad I didn't
have to pick up a gun. I'm glad I didn't get killed or kill
somebody,'' he said. ``I hope my kids enjoy the same lack of
manhood.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	   ROCHESTER, Minnesota. (AP) _ Jordan's King Hussein plans to stay
at the Mayo Clinic for more tests nearly a week after spells of
high fever.
	   ``His fever has been brought under control and he's feeling
better,'' hospital spokeswoman Jane Jacobs said Monday.
	   She did not know how long he would remain here.
	   The 62-year-old king left for Minnesota on July 14, telling
state-run television he had been having high fevers three times a
day.
	   Jordanian doctors said last week they thought the king's illness
was a recurrence of a bout of bacteria that attacked his lymph
glands in October, when he suffered fever, fatigue and weight loss.
	   ___
	   LONDON (AP) _ Talk about devotion.
	   Kevin Spacey is taking a night off from his marathon London
stage role in Eugene O'Neill's ``The Iceman Cometh'' to undertake a
separate kind of marathon: heading to Los Angeles for the premiere
Wednesday of his film ``The Negotiator'' and then back to London in
time for his play on Thursday.
	   Spacey was scheduled to perform as usual Tuesday night his
highly acclaimed performance at the Old Vic playing anguished
salesman, Hickey.
	   The next morning, he was to take the Concorde to New York and
change to a plane for Los Angeles. After the premiere, he flies
back to New York in time for the morning Concorde back to London on
Thursday. That flight in turn gets him to Heathrow Airport a scant
90 minutes before Thursday's performance of the play starts.
	   ``Hopefully, nothing will be delayed,'' said Spacey, adding that
he and his colleagues ``have a good ending of the first act if I'm
not there.''
	   Spacey has agreed to an extra performance of the play on Sunday
_ the Oscar-winning actor's 39th birthday _ to make up for the
missed show. The sellout run of ``Iceman'' ends Aug. 1.
	   ``The Negotiator'' opens across the United States on July 29.
</TEXT>
