<SLUG> BC-Today In History,0561 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Monday, July 27
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   Today is Monday, July 27, the 208th day of 1998. There are 157
days left in the year.
	   Highlights in history on this date:
	   1563 - French army regains Le Havre, France, where English
garrison is stricken with plague. Soldiers returning to England
introduce the plague.
	   1655 - Great Elector of Brandenburg concludes defense treaty
with Dutch, which starts first Northern War when Sweden's King
Charles X invades Poland.
	   1675 - French Marshal Turenne is killed in battle at Sassbach,
marking end of great French victories against Triple Alliance
forces.
	   1710 - British forces score victory over Spanish at Alminara,
Spain.
	   1795 - Spain signs peace treaty with France, ceding her part of
Santo Domingo.
	   1839 - Opium War between China and Britain begins after Chinese
authorities seize and burn British cargoes of opium.
	   1848 - Russians invade Danubian principalities at request of
Turkey to put down revolts there.
	   1894 - Regent of Korea declares war on China.
	   1933 - Assyrian Christians are massacred in Iraq.
	   1941 - Japanese forces land in Indochina during World War II.
	   1953 - Korean armistice is signed at Panmunjom.
	   1954 - Britain and Egypt agree on terms ending 72 years of
British control of Suez Canal.
	   1965 - U..S. planes carry out first attacks against
anti-aircraft missile sites in North Vietnam.
	   1978 - U.N. Security Council endorses Western plan for ending
guerrilla warfare in South-West Africa and making it independent as
new black African state of Namibia.
	   1987 - Riot police in Sri Lanka clash with Sinhalese Buddhists,
demonstrating against peace plan aimed at ending bloody rebellion
by Tamil Hindus.
	   1988 - Iraq continues to insist on face-to-face negotiations
with Iran before starting any cease-fire in Gulf War.
	   1990 - Philippine miners rescue two people who had been trapped
for eleven days following hotel collapse during earthquake that
struck Baguio, killing at least 1,600.
	   1991 - South Africa's latest labor movement threatens strike and
tax boycott to protest secret government payments to Inkatha
Freedom Party.
	   1992 - The first airbus stolen during the Iraqi occupation
returns to Kuwait.
	   1993 - A bomb rips through downtown Milan, killing at least five
people and wounding seven.
	   1994 - Bosnian Serbs ambush a U.N. convoy as it approaches a
road into Sarajevo, killing one British soldier and wounding
another.
	   1995 - In Pakistan, army troops and rescue workers battle to
evacuate tens of thousands of flood victims as monsoon rains pound
much of the nation.
	   1996 - A pipe bomb explodes in Centennial Olympic Park in
Atlanta, killing one person and injuring more than 100.
	   1997 - Typhoon Rosie hits Japan, killing at least two persons.
	   Today's Birthdays:
	   Edward Montagu, English admiral (1625-1672); Ernst Dohnanyi,
Hungarian composer (1877-1960); Norman Lear, U.S. TV producer
(1922--); Robert Holmes a Court, South Africa-born Australian
businessman (1937-1990); Allan Border, Australian cricketer
(1955--); Bobbie Gentry, U.S singer (1944--) Maureen McGovern, U.S.
singer (1949--).
	   Thought For Today:
	   He who is learned is not wise; He who is wise is not learned _
From the Tao (dow) Te Ching, the sacred book of Taoism.
</TEXT>
