<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Papua New Guinea-Tsunami-Jungle Survivors </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tsunami survivors huddle in the jungle
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Papua New Guinea-Tsunami

<TEXT>
	   VANIMO, Papua New Guinea (AP) _ They are huddled in small groups
deep in the jungle, far away from the sea that claimed so many of
their loved ones and friends.
	   These are the lost people of Sissano, the survivors of one of
the century's most catastrophic tsunami that four days ago washed
away villages where up to 10,000 people lived.
	   They are not hungry or in most cases even badly sick. They are
simply afraid that another wave with the roar of a jet and the
power of a bomb will engulf them.
	   No one knows how many there are, but as the bodies of their
loved ones and neighbors bloat and bleach in the Sissano lagoon and
along the beach of death, they wait.
	   Tas Maketu, a senior staffer with former prime minister and
elder statesman Sir Michael Somare, says the people will not come
out until someone they trust tells them there will be no more tidal
waves.
	   Maketu has spent all his life in Nimas village, one of four that
were located between the Bismark Sea and the Sissano lagoon on the
edge of the ``ring of fire'' volcanic belt around the Pacific
Ocean.
	   The remains of all four villages and many of their residents can
be seen floating in the lagoon.
	   ``Our church was imported from Germany and stood for 80 years,
but now it and everything else is gone,'' Maketu said.
	   A tear wells in his eye as he remembered his mother. She also
survived for about 80 years in Nimas, but the wave took her as
well.
	   Maketu will spend Wednesday night in the bush with his people,
trying to reassure them and to encourage them out of their jungle
hideouts.
	   ``I don't think they will listen. They can hunt and gather food
and there is plenty of good water so they might stay away for a
long time.''
	   One thing they won't eat is their normal luxury food, wild boar.
Those scavengers, along with the village dogs, have been feasting
on the remains of the dead.
	   Small patrols from the Papua New Guinea army, with Australian
military help, are searching for the lost people of Sisano there is hope.
	   On Tuesday, two 9-year-old girls were found alive on the beach
that bore the brunt of the giant wave. Later in the day nine more
people were found alive and reasonably well amongst the mangroves
where they had washed up miles (kms) from their villages.
	   As Tas Maketu put it, the disaster has destroyed the fabric of
village life for an estimated 10,000 people.
	   ``It has destroyed the very heart of our village way of life.
Our oral history and many of the next generation are gone
forever,'' he said. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
