<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Philippine Airlines </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine Airlines ground crew union goes on strike
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous; RECASTS throughout with more details &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Ground personnel at ailing Philippine
Airlines went on strike Wednesday, demanding the company recall
thousands of workers who were laid off during a recent devastating
pilots' strike.
	   ``The strike will last until the airline closes unless PAL
changes its position and recalls the retrenched workers,'' ground
crew union president Alex Barrientos told The Associated Press.
``We will not stop the strike.''
	   PAL has said a strike by its ground personnel could force Asia's
oldest airline to close down after 57 years of operation.
	   The airline said it had canceled all but two of its flights
Wednesday.
	   Philippine Airlines ground crew also service other carriers such
as China Airlines, Singapore Airlines and Northwest Airlines,
according to radio reports.
	   In June, PAL was embroiled in a crippling three-week pilots'
strike that brought the company close to financial ruin.
	   At the height of the strike, PAL laid off 5,000 of its nearly
14,000 workers to minimize its losses.
	   The ground personnel union then threatened to go on strike to
demand the reinstatement of the terminated workers but the labor
department assumed jurisdiction of the union's dispute with PAL on
July 10 and prohibited any work stoppage.
	   The labor department also ordered the airline to suspend any
more layoffs.
	   The union, however, said it would go ahead with the strike
plans.
	   Barrientos said union and company officials met the past two
nights to discuss a possible compromise involving the return of all
5,000 laid-off workers, to be followed by a formalized retrenchment
plan. However, the talks broke down Tuesday night, he said.
	   The union filed a second strike notice with the labor department
Tuesday afternoon charging an illegal lockout, union busting and
termination of union officers.
	   PAL senior vice president Avelino Zapanta said management can't
give in to the workers' demand since the airline already has
whittled down its operations following the pilots' strike.
	   PAL says it is unable to make payments on about dlrs 2 billion
of debt and is discussing a rehabilitation program with Manila's
Securities and Exchange Commission.
	   SEC chairman Perfecto Yasay expressed pessimism Wednesday over
whether that plan would be viable with the strike by ground
personnel. 	   
</TEXT>
