<HEADER>
w1416 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANALYSIS-Nigeria'sCyn     07-21 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANALYSIS-Nigeria's Cynicism,0628 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nigerian leader promises democracy, so why do Nigerians shrug?
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; An AP News Analysis &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo LON114 of July 20 &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) _ It was a sweeping announcement,
replete with denunciations of the former dictator's plans, the
abolishment of politically subservient parties, a promise of free
elections and a return to civilian rule for Nigeria.
	   For a country in search of democracy, there wasn't much more
that Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar could have promised.
	   But the announcement left Nigerians used to years of crippling
military rule with several questions: Why did Abubakar set no date
for presidential elections, and why is the transition planned for
the end of next May instead of earlier?
	   This West African nation, the continent's most populous, has
heard countless promises of democracy in its 38 years of
independence. Even its most callous dictators quickly learn the
tunes of empty political promises. Gen. Sani Abacha, the dictator
whose death last month ushered Abubakar into power, staged his 1993
coup and quickly promised real democracy _ later.
	   In reality, though, Nigeria's post-colonial political history
has been a litany of coups and military rulers. Nigerians, in turn,
have become a people steeped in political cynicism.
	   So it was no surprise that reaction to Abubakar's announcement
Monday night was mixed, a combination of wait-and-see optimism and
utter disdain. The government's most ardent critics are furious
that no interim government was quickly brought in, and will have to
wait for elections Abubakar promised for the first quarter of 1999.
	   Much of the praise for the speech came from average Nigerians,
who saw more hope in promises of pay reform and better telephone
systems than in vows of democracy.
	   To many Nigerians, Abubakar's vows will remain empty promises
until he actually follows through.
	   But Abubakar has been warmly welcomed by Nigeria's international
critics and his speech was one more reason for praise. And it was
the West, in part, that Abubakar was addressing.
	   He rules a country that should be living the good life, thriving
on huge oil reserves. Instead, corruption, neglect and political
isolation have crippled the country, and only a tiny percentage of
Nigerians live well. With the West's help _ from debt relief and
trade agreements to an end to travel restrictions on junta leaders
_ Abubakar knows his country could flourish.
	   Abubakar does have an established track record. He has freed
dozens of political prisoners and met with some of the country's
best-known opposition leaders. He admits that corruption has harmed
his country.
	   He also has risked alienating his fellow soldiers, some of whom
would pay a financial price by the rise of a civilian government.
The corruption-driven income that has made many generals rich would
suddenly be cut off.
	   Abubakar apparently doesn't fear his fellow generals. Most of
the pro-Abacha military claque has been farmed out to the
provinces, retired or has simply disappeared from view.
	   The danger for Abubakar if he fails to deliver will be from the
other side of Nigerian society _ the people who could take to the
streets in revolt.
	   In Nigeria, political troubles have traditionally been met more
often with grumbling complacency than revolt. But the country did
see days of rioting earlier this month following the death of
Moshood Abiola, the apparent winner of 1993's presidential
elections who had been jailed since 1994.
	   And Nigerians insist they will not accept another Abacha-style
leader.
	   ___
	   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Abidjan-based Tim Sullivan reports on Africa for
The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-ANALYSIS-Nigeria's Cynicism; CT:i; 
