<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Goodwill-Gymnastics,0339 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Atler wins Goodwill gold
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HAL BOCK &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNIONDALE, New York (AP) _ Best in the vault in the United
States, Vanessa Atler added a Goodwill Games gold medal Tuesday
night.
	   And she thought she could have done better.
	   Atler, who is also the U.S. national champion in the all-around,
scored 9.662 as the second gymnast on the vault.
	   ``I didn't think it would stand up,'' she said. ``I thought I'd
be fifth.''
	   Throughout, though, Atler, from Canyon Country, Calif., stayed
in front and claimed the gold medal over six other competitors.
	   ``My performance on a 1-to-10 was maybe an 8,'' she said. ``It
was not spectacular. I thought I did well and I was proud of
myself, but I still felt there was room for improvement.''
	   The silver medal went to Elena Dolgopolova of Russia with 9.600.
Simona Amanar of Romania, winner of the bronze in the all-around
competition on Sunday, took another bronze in the vault with a
9.587.
	   In the men's floor exercise, Alexei Nemov of Russia won the gold
with a score of 9.725. American Jay Thornton of Augusta, Ga., took
the silver with 9.550 and the bronze went to Alexei Bondarenko of
Russia with 9.525.
	   For Nemov, the reigning world and European champion in floor
exercise, it was an impressive recovery after a disappointing
seventh in the men's all-around on Monday. He had scored well in
the opening floor routine with a 9.450 but struggled after that.
	   It was Bondarenko's second medal of the competition. He won a
silver in the all-around.
	   American Sean Townshend of Houston fell and tumbled out of
bounds in the floor routine and finished last among the eight
gymnasts with 8.450.
	   Lan Sang of China was injured during warmups on the vault and
was forced to withdraw.
	   Dominique Moceanu of the United States and Ivan Ivankov of
Belarus, winners of the Goodwill all-around gold medals on the
first two nights of the games, did not compete on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
