w1440 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Algeria-UNMission     07-21 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Algeria-UN Mission,0732 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Unprecedented mission, but will access be adequate?
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ELAINE GANLEY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ A U.N. delegation is heading to Algeria on an
unprecedented mission seeking the sources of more than six years of
bloodshed. But questions remain over the group's ability to conduct
its investigation.
	   The two-week mission, beginning Wednesday, comes against a
backdrop of new violence in the north African country. More than 50
people were killed in three days last week, including two
sunbathers killed in a new form of violence: bombs hidden under the
sand on Mediterranean beaches.
	   The presence of the six-member delegation, led by former
Portuguese President Mario Soares, represents a breakthough in
international efforts to carry out an independent inquiry into the
violence in Algeria, which has taken an estimated 75,000 lives
since 1992.
	   The North African nation long resisted an inquiry, saying such a
probe would amount to interference in the country's internal
affairs.
	   Authorities blame the bloodshed on Islamic insurgents waging a
terror campaign to topple the military-backed government.
	   But suspicions have been raised that security forces or
government-armed militias may have had at least a passive role in
violence. Such questions led to pressure from the United States and
other nations for an independent investigation.
	   The big question is how much freedom of movement the delegation
will be allowed.
	   Can delegates visit massacre sites _ access denied a European
parliamentary delegation last February _ and will they meet with
leaders of the banned Islamic Salvation Front, a potentially
critical source of information?
	   U.N. spokesman Juan Carlos Brandt said earlier this month that
delegates have been assured ``free and complete access to all
sources of information.''
	   But Algeria's Foreign Ministry spokesman, Abdelaziz Sbaa, made
clear Tuesday that members of the mission are not to contact those
``outside the law,'' an apparent reference to the Salvation Front.
	   Soares, in a telephone interview Monday with The Associated
Press in Lisbon, suggested that Algerian authorities may have a say
in setting the agenda.
	   ``When we get there, we'll discuss with the authorities what
they want and what we want and we'll take it from there,'' Soares
said, declining to give further information.
	   The Salvation Front's imminent victory in January 1992
legislative elections led to a military coup. The army aborted the
voting, dismissed President Chadli Bendjedid and carried out a
brutal crackdown on Muslim fundamentalists.
	   That move triggered the insurgency and a self-perpetuating cycle
of violence.
	   Just last week, up to 21 people in a village near Tiaret, 250
kms (150 miles) southwest of Algiers, were reported massacred by
armed men in a scenario that has become customary. Less usual was
the late-night attack Saturday on an army barracks in the Chlef
mountains, 200 kms (125 miles) south of Algiers.
	   Most startling were the bombs hidden in sand at beaches in Rais
Hamidou, near Algiers, and Tipaza, further down the coast. The
unprecedented attacks Friday killed at least two sunbathers.
	   The outside world has been largely shielded from the true
nature, and extent, of the violence. Algerian media accounts are
controlled and visas difficult to obtain for foreign journalists,
whose movements there are controlled.
	   The New York-based group Human Rights Watch said Tuesday the
visit shouldn't be seen as a substitute for more in-depth
investigations by U.N. human rights experts.
	   Algeria has steadfastly rejected claims of serious human rights
problems despite reports by human rights groups of torture,
disappearances, extrajudicial killings and other atrocities.
	   U.N. human rights experts in Geneva expressed dismay after
concluding a review this week of Algeria's report on its human
rights situation. Committee members said queries had not been
adequately addressed.
	   ``What we are looking for are some answers,'' said Thomas
Buergenthal, of the United States.
	   Accompanying Soares are: former Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral, former Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul-Karim Kabariti,
the attorney-general of Kenya, Amos Wako, the former American U.N.
ambassador Donald McHenry, and Simone Veil, France's former health
minister. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Algeria-UN Mission; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
