w1441 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-Markets     07-21 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar higher, Tokyo stocks fall in early trading
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar was higher against the yen early
Wednesday as Tokyo stock prices opened lower, prompting Japanese
and overseas investors to buy back the U.S. currency.
	   The dollar bought 140.24 yen in early trading, up 0.76 yen from
late Tuesday in Tokyo but below its late New York rate of 140.40
yen overnight.
	   Traders said the yen came under pressure as a fall in the shares
of the troubled Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan also hurt sentiment.
	   LTCB shares have dropped dramatically in the last two months
amid rumors the bank was having trouble staying afloat, raising
renewed concern over Japan's financial system.
	   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan's comments indicating
that the Fed had no plans to lower interest rates in the short term
also supported the dollar.
	   Greenspan made the remarks in mid-year testimony before the
Senate Banking Committee on Tuesday. His comments dashed traders'
hopes the Fed might reduce interest rates to stimulate the economy
if it falters.
	   On the stock market, an overnight tumble on Wall Street was
having a negative effect on the Tokyo market. The Dow Jones
industrial average closed at 9,190.19 points on Tuesday, down
105.56.
	   In Tokyo, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 115.68 points,
or 0.70 percent, to 16,441.01 points in the first 30 minutes of
trading. On Tuesday, the average lost 14.09 points, or 0.09
percent.
	   The market was also being hurt by concerns that Foreign Minister
Keizo Obuchi will win the ruling Liberal Democratic Party's
election Friday for its next president, who will succeed Ryutaro
Hashimoto as prime minister.
	   ``What the market wants is drastic financial reforms, but Obuchi
seems to lack the ability to launch such reforms,'' said Sachio
Ishikawa, general manager of the stock division at Chuo Securities.
	   Opinion polls show greater public support for Health Minister
Junichiro Koizumi and veteran politician Seiroku Kajiyama. But the
mathematics of LDP factional politics suggest Obuchi is leading the
race, Japanese newspapers reported Wednesday.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 9.89 points, or 0.77 percent, to 1,267.28.
On Tuesday, the TOPIX closed down 0.78 points, or 0.06 percent, the
day before.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond fell to 1.400 percent from Tuesday's finish of
1.415 percent, driving its price up to 110.39 yen from 110.30 yen.
 &UR; (km)
</TEXT>
