w1452 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-Yemen-IntrepidTra     07-21 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Yemen-Intrepid Travelers,0819 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kidnappings, restive tribesmen _ and booming tourism _ in Yemen
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo SAN101 &QL; 
 &UR; By ANTHONY SHADID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ In a travel brochure, it might give a
prospective tourist nightmares: a destination with three times as
many weapons as people, fearsome tribesmen with a nasty penchant
for kidnapping foreigners and a rugged outback well beyond the law.
	   In Yemen, despite all that _ and perhaps, just perhaps, because
of it _ tourism is booming. The number of visitors to the land of
the Queen of Sheba has doubled in three years, bringing dlrs 69
million to one of the Arab world's poorest countries.
	   For the daring, who come mostly from Europe, Yemen offers a
window on history, ancient but still stunning cities where caravans
of antiquity took on spices and incense. The country's coral reefs
are pristine, its mountains awesome.
	   ``Here, you discover the beauty of the country, the beaches, the
desert, the sea and the unique architecture,'' said Yahya Othman,
who organizes tours for Arabian Horizons in San`a, the capital.
	   But you might discover kidnappers, too.
	   Tribesmen across lawless swaths of Yemen have abducted more than
250 foreigners since 1991, often in broad daylight. The German
ambassador's daughter, a 3-year-old South Korean girl and a group
of seven Italians were among victims of this replay of traditional
tribal hostage-taking.
	   Kidnappers' demands range from compensation for money lost to a
crooked car dealer to freedom for kinsmen arrested for earlier
abductions. Often, they simply want more government services in
their neglected regions. Every tourist was released unharmed,
usually after a few days of rigorous bargaining.
	   But the problem remains _ what to do about the kidnappings?
	   Omar M. Omar, an owner of Universal Touring, one of Yemen's
largest tour companies, has his own solution. He pays the tribes
off _ sometimes as much as dlrs 150 for a convoy of three or four
cars. During peak season, the bribes may cost him dlrs 7,350 a
month.
	   ``I write the checks myself,'' he said, grinning.
	   His company even wrote tour operators a letter this month
titled, ``Kidnappings in Yemen: Myth and Reality.''
	   The abductions seem to have little effect on tourism. About
84,000 visitors came in 1997, the peak year for kidnappings. In
fact, in every year since 1994 that abductions increased, so did
tourism.
	   Othman lost two tourists one night to tribesmen in the northern
city of Saada, famous for its silver jewelry and situated on an old
caravan route. He said they emerged the next morning invigorated
after the kidnappers slaughtered a goat in their honor.
	   ``Some people ask me, `Can you arrange a kidnapping tour?''' he
said. ``I don't know if they're joking or telling the truth. Maybe
some of them are serious, but we can't do it.''
	   The tourists themselves take it in stride. Many are from a hardy
lot who have toured much of the Middle East.
	   Some say they were drawn by the towers of Hadrawmawt Valley,
where buildings of mud, straw and dung can rise eight stories.
Others are attracted to the soaring minarets frosted with gypsum in
San`a. Ma'rib, the ancient capital of Sheba, enchants others.
	   And few, it seems, prepare for possible trouble.
	   ``If you mean malaria tablets, yes, but that's the only
precaution we took. We don't carry a weapon,'' said Nancy
Passchier, a Dutch tourist visiting a palace improbably perched
atop a 60-foot-high (18-meter) outcropping outside San`a.
	   Kidnappings are not Yemen's only scourge. In provinces where
every man and more than a few boys carry a dagger and rifle,
tribesmen have escalated their fight with a government they believe
has failed to provide them with hospitals, schools and roads.
	   On Tuesday, tribesmen opened fire on a convoy carrying Yemen's
interior minister and other officials, injuring a provincial
governor and six security guards. A tribal leader said the ambush
was carried out by tribesmen protesting a 40 percent government
hike in fuel prices.
	   Protests had rocked Yemeni cities last month when the government
raised the fuel prices. And a simmering border dispute with Saudi
Arabia has threatened to flare up.
	   Government officials have promised to tighten security, saying
they will send bigger forces into lawless regions and propose
legislation to execute kidnappers.
	   But they say the violence can only dent a growing industry.
Tourism brings in 13 percent of government revenue, and Abdul Malek
Mansour, the tourism and culture minister, wants it to reach 50
percent in five years.
	   ``Oil runs out eventually,'' he said, ``but the supply of
tourists will never be exhausted.''
	   His ministry has begun publishing glossy, professional brochures
with maps, pictures and history.
	   The slogan on one: ``Yemen, be ready to be astounded.''
</TEXT>
