w1458 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-Lithuania-Landsbe     07-21 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Lithuania-Landsbergis Fades,0634 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lithuanian independence hero loses luster
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos NY305-306 &QL; 
 &UR; By LIUDAS DAPKUS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VILNIUS, Lithuania (AP) _ Ten years ago, Vytautas Landsbergis
galvanized his countrymen's desires for freedom from Soviet
domination and led them on the road to independence.
	   Today, most see him as an awkward relic. From the height of
popularity, he has fallen to being one of the country's
most-criticized politicians.
	   With the founding of the Sajudis movement in June 1988,
Landsbergis became the Baltic states' most prominent dissident. To
the West, he was the embodiment of the changes shaking the Soviet
Union into collapse.
	   Landsbergis' charisma stemmed from his prickly dignity, his
absolute confidence in his own beliefs and his gift for vivid,
moralizing rhetoric _ the same qualities that now plague him in his
political decline.
	   While grateful to him for fearlessly standing up to the Kremlin,
many Lithuanians now find Landsbergis' adamant approach out of step
with the country's nascent democracy, where compromise and
cooperation are more important than rigid determination.
	   ``Destiny gave him a great chance to become a political leader
in such an exciting time, but this opportunity was spoiled by his
own character,'' says Kazimieras Motieka, a former Landsbergis
ally.
	   How far Landsbergis, the speaker of Parliament, has fallen was
painfully clear in December's presidential election. He finished a
distant third behind two political newcomers, including winner
Valdas Adamkus, a Lithuanian-American regarded with wide skepticism
because he had lived abroad for more than 50 years.
	   Reflecting the differences between Lithuania's new and old
waves, Adamkus on July 10 vetoed a Landsbergis-drafted law that
would have denied a wide range of government and private jobs to
former KGB operatives.
	   In a poll published in June by the respected newspaper Lietuvos
Rytas, respondents gave Landsbergis the second-lowest approval
rating among 30 top politicians.
	   The 65-year-old Landsbergis' luster has been tarnished by a
number of incidents.
	   He lost much standing with Lithuanian news media after proposing
a government agency be set up to monitor the portrayal of sex and
violence on television _ a move criticized as tantamount to forming
a censorship board.
	   He met the opposition in a typically caustic way. ``It seems to
me that Lithuanian society is not mature enough for the proposals
we made,'' he said at the time.
	   Last year, he embarrassed many Lithuanians when he complained
the European Union's failure to invite their country to join was
like the Soviet-Nazi Germany pact that divided Europe into spheres
of influence.
	   His reputation was further hurt this spring when news reports
said he was behind an alleged Interior Ministry program to carry
out surveillance of journalists, political leaders and their
families.
	   The ministry unit that reportedly did the work has been
disbanded, but the controversy continues in the press and confirms
many people's belief that Landsbergis is a potentially disruptive
remnant of a more suspicious time.
	   ``Landsbergis does not have a serious political future,'' says
Rimvydas Valatka, political analyst at the newspaper Lietuvos
Rytas.
	   ``He has made the mistake of relying on a limited segment of
society for support and he cannot accept anyone who does not agree
with him 100 percent. His elderly electorate is dying out and the
younger generation will not accept someone who dictates to them.''
	   Landsbergis, however, expresses confidence he is on the right
track.
	   ``I also heard questions about whether I was tired of politics
in 1991 and 1992,'' he says. ``I did not go then, nor I am I going
to go now.'' 	   
</TEXT>
