<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Northern Ireland,0415 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Talks between marchers and residents break up without agreement
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS pvs. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ A third round of talks aimed at
resolving a standoff between Protestant marchers and security
forces blocking them from parading through a hostile Catholic
neighborhood has broken up without agreement.
	   But go-betweens said some progress had been made at Tuesday
night's talks between the Orange Order and residents of Garvaghy
Road in Portadown, 40 miles (65 kilometers) northwest of Belfast.
	   Police and soldiers, enforcing an order by the
government-appointed Parades Commission, prevented members of the
Orange Order from marching down the Garvaghy Road on July 5.
	   Orangemen gathered on a nearby hillside every night for a week,
underlining their determination to follow their traditional parade
route. But the number of protesters fell after arsonists killed
three young sons of a Catholic woman July 12 in the town of
Ballymoney, 40 miles (65 kms) northwest of Belfast.
	   Thomas Robert Garfield Gilmour, 23, of Ballymoney appeared in
court Tuesday on charges of murdering the Quinn brothers _ Richard
11, Mark, 10, and Jason, 9 _ in the firebombing. He denied the
charges and denied being a member of any paramilitary organization.
	   Gilmour was ordered jailed until a court appearance on Aug. 12.
	   A number of people are being held for questioning in the case,
but police declined Tuesday to give a specific number.
	   Police believe the family was targeted because the boy's mother,
29-year-old Chrissie Quinn, was a Catholic who lived with a
Protestant boyfriend.
	   The attack was the worst incident of violence during the
standoff, in which churches were burned, vehicles set ablaze, homes
firebombed and police pelted with gasoline bombs. Police used
plastic bullets to repel protesters who attacked them and tried to
breach the barriers separating them from the Catholic neighborhood.
	   Stunned by the killings of the Quinn brothers, some leaders of
the Orange Order called for an end to the confrontation between its
marchers and security forces.
	   The talks were set up 10 days ago at the height of the
confrontation.
	   On Tuesday, the two delegations remained in separate rooms, with
officials shuttling communications between them.
	   Garvaghy Road residents criticized the Orange delegation for
refusing to meet them face to face but said they remained open to
continuing the process.
</TEXT>
