<SLUG> BC-Japan-Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's trade surplus rises in June, first half of 1998
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with details &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's trade surplus with the world jumped 27
percent in June for the 15th straight month and soared 66 percent
during the first six months of the year, the government said
Wednesday.
	   The merchandise trade surplus, a tally of goods exported minus
imports, rose to 1.22 trillion yen (dlrs 8.68 billion) in June from
the same period last year, the Finance Ministry said.
	   Exports _ buoyed mostly by increased auto shipments to the
United States and Europe _ rose 5.2 percent to 4.36 trillion yen
(dlrs 31.1 billion), it said. Imports fell 1.4 percent to 3.12
trillion yen (dlrs 22.2 billion).
	   Still, the ministry said the pace of growth in the trade surplus
last month was the slowest in more than a year.
	   The increase in the surplus _ which is measured as goods pass
customs but before adjustment for seasonal factors _ was also
moderately lower than economists had forecast.
	   Japan's politically sensitive surplus with the United States,
meanwhile, climbed for the 21st straight month, rising 48.6 percent
in June to 555.58 billion yen (dlrs 4.0 billion).
	   The trade surplus has been rising as Japan has increased its
reliance on exports to pull itself out of a prolonged slump. The
weak domestic economy has also crimped demand for foreign goods.
	   Japan has come under increasing pressure to revive its
recession-plagued economy and help struggling Asian nations by
importing more from the region.
	   In a sign of the regional economic troubles, Japan's trade
surplus with Asia dropped 36.3 percent in June to 374.3 billion yen
(dlrs 2.7 billion).
	   Also Wednesday, the Finance Ministry said that for the first six
months of 1998, Japan's surplus with the world rose 66 percent on
the year to 6.567 trillion yen (dlrs 46.8 billion).
	   With the United States, Japan posted a six-month surplus of
3.074 trillion yen (dlrs 21.9 billion), up 37.7 percent from last
year.
