<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Stocks fall sharply in morning trading, dollar higher in Tokyo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with midday stocks, late morning bond and currency
prices &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese stocks fell sharply in early trading
Wednesday on worry about the outcome of a ruling party contest to
select a new prime minister. The dollar rose against the yen.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average declined 220.38
points, or 1.33 percent, to 16,336.31 as of midday. On Tuesday, the
average lost 14.09 points, or 0.09 percent.
	   Stocks were sold off on concern that Foreign Minister Keizo
Obuchi will win a three-way race to succeed outgoing Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto. The ruling party plans to elect a new president
Friday, who will then become the next prime minister.
	   ``What the market wants is drastic financial reforms, but Obuchi
seems to lack the ability to launch such reforms,'' said Sachio
Ishikawa, general manager of the stock division at Chuo Securities
Co.
	   Opinion polls show greater public support for Health Minister
Junichiro Koizumi and veteran politician Seiroku Kajiyama. But the
mathematics of ruling party factional politics suggest that Obuchi
is leading the race, Japanese newspapers reported Wednesday.
	   Led lower by bank stocks, the broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of
all issues listed on the first section lost 14.66 points, or 1.15
percent, to 1,262.51. On Tuesday, the TOPIX closed down 0.78
points, or 0.06 percent, the day before.
	   A sharp drop overnight on Wall Street also weighed on the Tokyo
market, traders said, where the Dow Jones Industrial Average closed
at 9,190.19 points on Tuesday, down 105.56.
	   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, meanwhile, the dollar
bought 140.66 yen in late morning trading, up 1.18 yen from late
Tuesday in Tokyo and also above its late New York rate of 140.40
yen overnight.
	   The U.S. currency strengthened as buying from investment trusts
offset dollar selling by overseas funds and Japanese exporters,
traders said.
	   In the fixed-income market, the yield on the benchmark No. 182
10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.420 percent from
Tuesday's finish of 1.415 percent, driving its price down to 110.25
yen from 110.30 yen.
 &UR; (km-cd-dj) 	   
</TEXT>
