<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Diseases </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dengue fever, malaria on the rise in Singapore
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Cases of dengue fever and malaria, the two most
common tropical mosquito-borne diseases, increased in Singapore
during the first half of the year, the country's Environment
Ministry said Wednesday.
	   The number of dengue fever cases rose by 800 to more than 2,800
between January and July this year, compared to the same period
last year.
	   Malaria cases also rose from 207 cases in the first half of
1997, to 236 cases in the same period this year. One person
succumbed to the parasitic disease last month.
	   Malaria is transmitted by the bite of a female Anopheles
mosquito. The Aedes mosquito can carry the dengue virus, which
causes fever, joint pains, chills and in some strains, brain
hemorrhaging and death.
	   Singapore has launched an island-wide campaign against the two
types of mosquitoes, with heavy fines for those who allow the
mosquitoes to breed on their property. 	   
</TEXT>
