<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Myanmar-Loggers Arrested </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Myanmar sentences 38 Thais to 20 years in jail for illegal logging
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ A Myanmar court has sentenced 38 Thais
to 20 years in jail each for illegally entering Myanmar and
engaging in illegal logging, Thailand's Bangkok Post reported
Wednesday.
	   The paper cited a district chief in northern Thailand as the
source of the information. Immediate confirmation was not available
from Myanmar's military government.
	   The 38 Thais were sentenced to five years each for illegally
entering Myanmar, and 15 years each for illegal logging. They were
tried and jailed in the town of Mong Hsat in Shan State, about 20
miles (32 kilometers) from the Thai border.
	   Thailand, which is severely deforested, has had a hardwood
logging ban in place since 1989. Most timber for Thai industries is
imported or smuggled from neighboring Myanmar and Cambodia.
	   Tensions between the two countries have risen sharply in recent
weeks after Thailand voiced concern over the deteriorating
political and human rights situation in Myanmar. 	   
</TEXT>
