<HEADLINE>
Salvadoran guardsman convicted in 1980 nuns' killing released on
</HEADLINE>
parole &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with comment by brother of slain
nun; inmate expected to be released from prison in San Vincente;
CHANGES attribution. &QL; 
 &UR; By EDITH BELTRAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN VICENTE, El Salvador (AP) _ A former national guardsman
convicted in the rapes and murders of three American nuns and a
layworker walked out of prison, paroled after serving 17 years of a
30-year prison sentence.
	   Jose Roberto Moreno Canjura, one of five guardsmen sentenced for
the crimes in 1984, left the La Esperanza prison four miles (six
kilometers) north of San Salvador after he was released Tuesday
under a new law intended to ease prison overcrowding.
	   A La Esperanza prison official confirmed that Moreno Canjura had
been released.
	   Moreno Canjura and the four other guardsmen were convicted of
kidnapping, raping and killing Roman Catholic nuns Ita Ford,
Dorothy Kazel and Maura Clark and layworker Jean Donovan on Dec. 2,
1980.
	   The crime caused outrage in United States, which strongly
supported the Salvadoran government during the 1980-1992 civil war.
The women were apparently killed because military-backed death
squads suspected them of sympathizing with leftist guerrillas.
	   The guardsmen have claimed in recent interviews that
``higher-ups'' ordered the killing of the four American church
workers.
	   Ford's brother said in a telephone interview late Tuesday that
the families of the slain women opposed the release.
	   ``The government of El Salvador should certainly not have
released these men before closely questioning them on ... who
ordered this crime and who covered it up,'' said William Ford of
Upper Montclair, New Jersey.
	   ``The people in jail were not the intellectual authors of the
murders. They were triggermen sent to do a job by someone else,''
he said.
	   Two more guardsmen are also eligible for parole under the new
law and may be released soon, one from a prison in San Vicente, 40
miles (65 kilometers) southeast of the capital. The other two did
not qualify for release because one previously had been convicted
on weapons charges and the other had participated in a prison
disturbance.
	   The guardsmen were sentenced to 30 years in prison in May 1984
and have been jailed since 1981. They were to be given credit for
time served before their convictions.
	   The U.S. State Department criticized the decision to order the
release of three national guardsmen when it was first announced in
June. The releases have been held up by appeals by prosecutors.
	   ``We think that's a bad idea,'' State Department spokesman James
P. Rubin said at the time, citing the ``heinous'' nature of the
crimes.
	   The national guard was disbanded after a 1992 peace agreement
ended the civil war, which killed an estimated 75,000 people.
</TEXT>
