u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PapuaNewGuinea-Tsunam 1stLd-Writethru   07-21 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Papua New Guinea-Tsunami, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Body-count worsens as corpses begin falling apart
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES 7th-8th grafs with relief worker comment.
 &UR; With BC-Papua New Guinea-Tsunami-Jungle Survivors
 &UR; AP Photos available
 &UR; By ROHAN SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VANIMO, Papua New Guinea (AP) _ Rescue workers Wednesday had
trouble counting the dead from a tsunami that wiped out coastal
villages in Papua New Guinea because rotting bodies were falling
apart and had to be gathered from a lagoon with nets.
	   The official death toll is over 1,200, but West Sepik provincial
governor John Tekwi told The Associated Press more than 3,000 died
as 23-foot (7-meter) earthquake-generated waves swept over
once-idyllic villages along 18 miles (30 km) of Papua New Guinea's
north coast last Friday.
	   Some 6,000 of the 8,000 to 10,000 people who lived in the area
are still missing, and Papua New Guinean Prime Minister Bill Skate
says he holds little hope many will be found alive.
	   ``Knowing the population base of the villages affected and the
people who are there, that is my conservative estimate,'' Tekwi
said.
	   ``At Warapu village, there were 3,000-plus (people), now there
are only 760. Where are the rest?'' he asked.
	   As of Tuesday, Skate said, only 2,527 people have been found
alive.
	   But Brother Jim Coucher, a relief worker from the Roman Catholic
Diocese of Vanimo, said Wednesday that more survivors had
apparently been found.
	   ``I heard yesterday there's 3,500 survivors -- and that's out of
a population of around about 8,000,'' Coucher said.
	   In Australia, the Salvation Army on Wednesday launched an appeal
for clothing for the survivors, but only called for adult clothes _
nearly all the children in the villages were killed by the deadly
waves.
	   Most of the confirmed dead and many of the missing are children,
victims of furious waters that nearly wiped out the next generation
of Papua New Guineans in the seconds it took to toss people into
trees, hurl them into a lagoon or pull them back into the ocean.
	   Most children were home on a holiday when the waves struck,
rather than in religious mission schools farther inland where they
might have been safe. So many children died that some schools were
not expected to reopen.
	   Now the dead are a threat to the living. Doctors fear new
outbreaks of disease could be caused by the thousands of bodies
rotting in the tropical heat.
	   Crocodiles, dogs and pigs are feasting on the cadavers, and
officials have sent out hunting parties to shoot the scavengers.
	   Burials gave way to gasoline-fueled cremations on the spot as
rescue and recovery workers found the rotting corpses falling apart
in the tropical heat as they tried to move them.
	   Skate on Tuesday invoked emergency powers under the constitution
to put Police Commissioner Peter Agilo in complete control of the
rescue and relief operation.
	   This was intended to end the chaotic scene at local airstrips
where dozens of light and medium aircraft, helicopters and military
planes jostle for runway space, with little or no air control.
	   Skate said stage one of the operation, finding and rescuing the
injured, was now almost complete.
	   Stage two, locating and burying the dead and preventing disease,
will begin with a more coordinated operation.
	   ``For three days we have been flat out. We haven't known what we
are doing. From today, the police commissioner will be in
control,'' Skate told a crowd at Sissano.
	   Skate had a good look at the cause of potential disease, the
hundreds of bloated bodies still drifting in the placid waters,
simmering in the tropical heat.
	   His boat passed more than a dozen bodies caught in the floating
debris of houses or impaled on tough mangrove roots.
	   ``We have to look at the environment, because it really could be
infested. The water is contaminated and it is very very unhealthy.
	   ``I have to sit with the National Disaster Committee and discuss
whether we should evacuate this area, otherwise we will have more
people who will get sick and eventually die,'' he said.
	   The thousands of people displaced by the tsunami have been
warned to stay away from the low-lying beach.
	   On shore, soldiers, missionaries, aid workers and the healthier
surviving villagers use spades to dig shallow graves in the sand,
then don surgical gloves to wrap the corpses in sheets of black
plastic.
	   The burials are unceremonious, with sand quickly shoveled in and
stamped down with their feet. Then the team moves on to the next
body, the next grave.
	   Papua New Guinea, with a population of 4 million, occupies the
eastern half of the island of New Guinea about 90 miles (145
kilometers) north of Australia. Some of its people live a
near-Stone Age existence in the jungles and swamps.
	   The remoteness of the region hampered emergency officials from
Australia, Papua New Guinea and New Zealand, who were coordinating
a rescue operation.
	   The first of three Royal Australian Air Force C-130 Hercules
transport aircraft arrived at Vanimo on Monday with emergency
supplies, including a field hospital and a 100-strong team of
doctors, nurses and engineers.
	   The medics set up a tent hospital on a sports field and cared
for victims sent by three overcrowded hospitals. Many survivors
underwent amputations because bacteria-filled coral sand had
infected wounds, causing gangrene, said Lt. Col. John Crozer, a
surgeon.
	   By Tuesday night, the Australian medics estimated they had dealt
with about 90 percent of the survivors who were injured. Not many
more survivors were expected to emerge from the jungle. 	   
</TEXT>
