<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Philippine Airlines, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine Airlines ground crew union goes on strike
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with impact on meeting of ASEAN foreign
ministers, President Estrada saying strike will hurt economy, PAL
warning strike may force its closure and delays at other airlines;
ADDS byline.
 &UR; AP Photos Staffing
 &UR; By JIM GOMEZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Ground personnel at ailing air
carrier Philippine Airlines went on strike Wednesday, demanding the
company recall thousands of workers who were laid off during a
recent pilots' strike.
	   The latest strike came as foreign ministers from the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations were preparing to arrive for an annual
meeting in Manila on Friday.
	   ``The strike will last until the airline closes unless PAL
changes its position and recalls the retrenched workers,'' ground
crew union president Alex Barrientos told The Associated Press.
``We will not stop the strike.''
	   PAL warned the strike could be a fatal blow for the troubled
flag carrier.
	   The 57-year-old airline, Asia's oldest, said it was forced to
cancel all but two of its flights Wednesday.
	   Its ground crew also service 19 out of 35 international carriers
at Manila's airport, including Japan Airlines, Singapore Airlines
and Northwest Airlines.
	   A Singapore Airlines official said flights were delayed by the
strike, with PAL caterers refusing to load food. Managers and a few
extra workers were handling passengers' baggage, she said.
	   Foreign ministers from Myanmar, Cambodia and Vietnam were
scheduled to arrive later Wednesday, with other ASEAN ministers set
to arrive Thursday.
	   Philippine President Joseph Estrada called the strike
unfortunate and said he hoped to meet with union officials.
	   ``This will have a big effect on our economy and on our
tourism,'' he said.
	   In June, PAL was embroiled in a crippling three-week pilots'
strike that brought the company close to financial ruin.
	   At the height of the strike, the flag carrier laid off 5,000 of
its nearly 14,000 workers to minimize its losses.
	   The ground personnel union then threatened to go on strike to
demand the reinstatement of the terminated workers, but the labor
department assumed jurisdiction of the dispute on July 10 and
prohibited any work stoppage.
	   The labor department also ordered the airline to suspend any
more layoffs.
	   The union, however, said it would go ahead with the strike
plans.
	   Union and company officials met Monday and Tuesday nights to
discuss a possible compromise involving a return of the laid-off
workers and review of the retrenchment plans. However, the airline
insisted the layoffs could be suspended only until Aug. 15, while
the union demanded an unconditional recall of the workers, with
talks on retrenchment to resume later, participants said.
	   PAL senior vice president Avelino Zapanta said management was
unable to give in to the union's demand for a return of the workers
since the airline already has slashed its operations following the
pilots' strike.
	   PAL says it is unable to make payments on about dlrs 2 billion
of debt and is discussing a rehabilitation program with Manila's
Securities and Exchange Commission.
	   The plan includes layoffs, the disposal of most of the airline's
planes, and a sharp reduction of flights.
	   SEC chairman Perfecto Yasay expressed pessimism Wednesday over
whether that plan would be viable with the strike by ground
personnel.	   
</TEXT>
