r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Thailand-Austria-Wate     07-21 0223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Austria-Water Pollution </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bangkok closes Austrian firm until it cleans up water supply
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Bangkok's Metropolitan Waterworks
Authority has ordered an Austrian company to close down until the
water it supplies to one of the city's districts is clean and free
from contaminants.
	   The MWA shut down Austria's Hydro Compact Company on July 17
because residents of Bang Phli district had been complaining since
March that their tap water was yellow and salty, an official with
the authority said Wednesday.
	   The official said the problem was caused by low fresh water
levels and contaminants from factories. Sea water had seeped into
canals used for the water supply, particularly during the hot
season which lasts from March through May, he said.
	   He added that the water was also being fouled by meat processing
plants in the area that were releasing waste water into the canals.
	   No lead or other chemical poisons were found in the water, said
the official who spoke only on condition of anonymity.
	   Hydro Compact Company was awarded a 15-year concession to supply
water to the district in 1990. The official said the closure was
only temporary until the problems were cleared up.
	   Until then, the MWA would supply the district with water from
other areas of Bangkok.	   
</TEXT>
